comment: "A man of cheerful yesterdays and confident tomorrows." "Mac" is a good student with lots of common sense. Stayed out a year but still intends to graduate with a good class. Has seen more practical work than many of the engineers.

name: Mack, Fay
comment: "A tender heart, a will inflexible." Always generous and never too busy to smile. Has decided views upon the smoking question. "Have you classified yet?" Her greatest trouble is in transferring her fussing credits from Grinnell. Has enough pep for half a dozen girls.

name: Macvicar, John
comment: "Falling in love is a matter of intermittent propinquity. The cure is propinquity." Another '14 who stayed out a year. Is now attending college in Ohio where his uncle stays, but we expect to see him back next semester. Never worries. Is a confirmed fusser.

name: Madson, Luella E.
comment: "The most manifest sign of wisdom is continued cheerfulness." Luella does even the smallest task assigned to her with all thoroughness, but is so modest about it all that few realize how indispensable she is. Always finds time for good grades. Never known to be downhearted.

name: Mattison, H. H.
comment: "To football lore, what's Phys. or Economics?" Matty came up from Penn College to be on hand to beat Iowa next year. His weight and ability to use it makes him a man hard to beat on the gridiron.

name: Meiggs, L. W.
comment: "What a voice was here now" He always says the right thing at the wrong time or something just as good. However, his studies and college activities are never neglected. A strong booster for South Dakota.

name: Meltzer, Chas.
comment: "The loud laugh that bespeaks the happy mind" The English faculty like "Sandy" so well that they keep him around continuously. Showed the boys up in the Sophomore judging contest.

name: Merritt, Worth
comment: "Beauty took vacation at the time of my creation" "Tubby" has an eye for business, and a faculty for working the "con" for a free ride. He is back in Campustry Lab and doesn't worry about college work.

name: Middleton, Amy L.
comment: "Just a smilin' face and a hearty hand, 'S religion 'at all folks understand." Quiet, but does things. If she be unobtrusive in campus activities, it is because of the place she so beautifully fills in her home. A graduate of I.S.T.C. and holds a teacher's life certificate.

name: Miller, Harold
comment: "I have always thought the action of men the best interpretation of their thoughts." A true Mohawk and proud of it. H. F.'s natural ability keeps him from brain fag, and brings him grades that would cause the common herd to suspect the Profs. of softening of the brain.

name: Miller, M. P.
comment: "Who mixed reason with pleasure and wisdom with mirth." "Philo" is a graduate of Princeton. His letters east usually require four cents postage. Samples ensilage for Evvard.

name: Miller, Robert J.
comment: "Some rolling stones gather great quantities of moss." "Bob" is long on stature, speech, and gray matter. Never placed a class in F. G. 21 wrong provided the professor was right.

name: Minges, George A.
comment: "As we advance in life we learn the limits of our abilities." George is a fusser at heart but has stifled his innermost yearnings and is one of the most earnest seekers after the why of things in the whole science division.

name: Minnis, C. Floyd
comment: "He shifts quite about then proceeds to expound, That it's merely the earth, not himself, that turns round." Minnis talks entirely too much for an engineer. He can argue, expound, diffuse, and otherwise liberate from his system more rhetoric with or without accompanying ideas than any self-respecting engineer should.

name: Montgomery, Mary E.
comment: "And privileged folks call her Mary." Moods are unknown to Mary. She gets good grades with little effort, taking a correspondence course with Cornell University.

name: Moore, Susie B.
comment: "My endeavors have ever come too short of my desire." With steadfast pluck unequaled by few, Mrs. Moore is gaining a fuller training for teaching in her chosen line of work. Came to Ames after trying other schools. Is bringing up her small son according to modern theories of eugenics.

name: Murphy, Mabel
comment: "A daughter of the gods, divinely tall and most divinely fair." A clever impersonator, who has little ways all her own. Would be recognized anywhere by her laughter. Fond of going to Ag. receptions. "A Swede by the name of Murphy."

name: Nielson, W. R.
comment: "The man who made Milwaukee famous" "Doc" believes in standing by the reputation of his town. Has had his troubles with the Sifting Committee, but is still on top.

name: Niles, Laura
comment: "And still the wonder grows, that one small head can carry all she knows" Laura doesn't believe in "putting off until tomorrow what you can do today." A shark in almost everything.

name: Noble, Nellie
comment: "If I chance to talk a little while, forgive me, I had it from my father" Given to pensive moods and dreamy solitudes. Is a loyal and sincere friend.

name: O'Connor, Mildred
comment: "She knits her brow—the only kind of fancy work this modern maid can do" Mildred came to us from Grinnell last year, and the '15s were glad to welcome her. Never spends Sunday out of town. Wonder why?

name: Ogilvie, Victor A.
comment: "He would be of a serious nature" His friends occasionally bring forth a smile in spite of "Vic's" best efforts at dignity. "Vic" studies when pressing engagements at Boone and Davis City do not prevent.

name: Olson, Norman E.
comment: "You might as well try to fatten a windmill by running oats through it" He likes watermelons and cross country but not on the same night. Ole is a Chem. fiend and the shark of the Junior Dairies. Always happy.

name: O'Rourke, John B.
comment: "With wisdom fraught, Not such as books, but such as practice taught." "Tim" is one of the few real engineers in the class with a fund of experience running from motors to groceries. Was held back at the start but will finish strong in the end.

name: Pammel, Doris
comment: "A foot more light, a step more true, Ne'er from the heath flower danced the dew." A light-hearted, lovable maiden who always does the unexpected. "Dozey" is an artist in designing gowns and studies "Vogue" diligently. She would rather dance than eat; is said to know something about the broken plaster on fifth floor Central.

name: Parle, Harry V.
comment: "He trudged along, unknowing what he sought, And whistled as he went, for want of thought." Looks like an owl but not nearly so wise. Works hard for what he gets. Not so widely known as some but admired by all his friends.

name: Paxon, P. B.
comment: Paxon uses the east window in Ag. Hall for a smoking room. A journalist of considerable repute. Changed his residence from Indiana to Iowa to save fifty dollars a year.

name: Pearce, G. T.
comment: "Church is a farce and holy men a bore" If he were half as "tuff" as he pretends to be, he would be a terror indeed. He believes that the road to Boone should be used much and often. A good wrestler.

name: Peaslee, O. M.
comment: "A bold attempt is half success" Peaslee has attempted lots of things since coming to Ames. This is his second try for a college education, while his ventures are without number.

name: Penick, Margaret
comment: Of softest manners, unaffected mind, Lover of peace, and friend of humankind. Margaret's friends are without number. In class she is always on the front seat, and her grades are envied and admired by all. Has a "stand-in" with instructors of the Ag. department in particular.

name: Perdue, H. S.
comment: "I have my three sorts of tobacco in my pocket, my light by me, and thus I begin." Passed up his A.H. at Texas Ag. "Purdy" makes frequent visits to Des Moines to see his sister. He is a bright student and an all-around good fellow.

name: Perry, Winifred
comment: "The nightingale dwells in her slender throat." This auburn-haired warbler finds much entertainment in helping "Preps" through the labyrinths of Botany Lab. Has an inexhaustible fund of anecdotes and is always on hand with a T.L. A brave, capable girl who accomplishes things.

name: Peters, J. H.
comment: "Language most shows a man speak that I may see thee." His sister's twin? Stays at Ames to keep the college music up to par. Circulates band literature. Julius believes in co-education. He has a great longing for wealth.

name: Peters, Eunice
comment: "When singleness is bliss, 'tis folly to be wise." At present has a weighty problem to solve. Wise but willing.

name: Peterson, Ward
comment: "Of modest demeanor, not addicted to frivolous things." Changed from E.E. to Ag. E. To pass up his course is Pete's one ambition. Never known to cast his eyes toward the feminine sex.

name: Peterson, Van D.
comment: "There should be more hours for pleasure and fewer for work." Tall and dignified, Van would pass easily for a bandmaster. Never makes much of a racket.

name: Phillips, Wilma A.
comment: "Paint me as I am." Passes up work with the least possible effort. Is mighty nice to her friends.

name: Pickford, A. H.
comment: "Every man has a fair turn to be as great as he pleases." "Pick" believes in "Science with practice," so never misses a campus lab. The handsome man who plays end on the Glee Club. Never had brain fatigue from overstudy.

name: Pierce, Jessie
comment: "Silence is one great art of conversation." One of the few who believes in saying to your face what she would not say in front of your back. At present is interested in the American national game.

name: Pittman, P. W.
comment: "As headstrong as an alligator on the banks of the Nile." His fun is the life of his classes. He can sleep more naturally during a recitation and wake up more abruptly with more dire results than any other student.

name: Porterfield, J. S.
comment: "There is scarcely any man who cannot persuade himself of his own merit." "Jack is the fellow who beats up the S.A.E.'s piano. Expects to get married as soon as the boys can spare him from the house."

name: Portlock, Kineta
comment: "I live, yet say not much, but think the more." Quiet and hardworking. Has beautiful brown eyes. After going to Iowa, has come to Ames to get an education.

name: Potter, E. G.
comment: "Say, fellows, have you seen Potter's sister?" Went to state university a year but decided to come to Ames immediately after the Ames-Iowa game of 1911. He's not so big, but what there is is all alive.

name: Potter, L. D.
comment: "Daws" is an easy-going sort of chap who doesn't make a big noise about anything. Is a booster for the Vet. course and is strong for keeping the girls at Ames.

name: Potter, L. P.
comment: A jolly good fellow, noted for his activities among the "fair sex." He finds time to attend classes occasionally between his visits to the post office. Was once an "Ag." but later joined the "loyal bunch" and is now waiting to become a real Dr.

name: Powell, Lester D.
comment: "Oh, I wouldn't lie to you." It took "Les" several years to decide whether he wanted to be a doctor at Iowa City or an Ag at Ames, but has finally come to believe that Ames is superior in more respects than just its railway connections to Omaha.

name: Price, Mary E.
comment: "Show me." Very reserved. Only those who know her appreciate her true worth and unselfish disposition. Won first prize for an I.S.C. "rah rah" song. A walking, living question mark.

name: Rackliffe, Arthur
comment: "I swear I have not changed my mind in twenty years." A man who believes the cow will feed the world. Art has been known to fuss but doesn't recommend the practice. A dairy cattle judge of rare ability.

name: Raeder, J. M.
comment: "My ancestors came over from Germany in the Mayflower." Jim is the chief crabber against thirty-five cent haircuts and short vacations. His grade-getting ability has obtained many a place for him.

name: Ramirez, Hipolito
comment: "A smile for every prof." Hippo has never yet been "stumped by a prof." His chief ambition is to start a commercial laboratory. Spent last summer running nitrogens and hexapoda.

name: Rath, R. A.
comment: "The pain of one maiden's refusal is drowned in the pain of the next." "Rube" has talent in any line he happens to take up. "Tommy" says he's crazy. Is sometimes known as "Dimples."

name: Reep, R. W.
comment: "Content to set the table in a roar." One of the solid men of the class. Has a knack of getting high grades and was never known to flunk. Always ready to hear a good story or tell one.

name: Reese, Vincent M.
comment: "He makes a solitude and calls it peace." So quiet that a ghost would seem noisy by comparison. Does his work and refuses to worry about results. Tried E.E. but decided to take a better course.

name: Reeve, Lew
comment: "Of making books there is no end, and much study is a weariness of the flesh." The leader of next year's Cyclones. Big and heavy and with lots of pep. Lew never saw the line he couldn't dent. Treats his work like he would an Iowa tackle. Never knocks.

name: Reeve, Myra R.
comment: "Of easy temper, naturally good." Never has caused any real excitement, except when she spilled a lot of pepper in cooking lab. Has the faculty of tending to her own affairs. A steady mover but never hurries.

name: Renne, Lysle W.
comment: "If at first you don't succeed, try, try again." Lysle believes in patronizing home industries. Trains the preps in a loud tone of voice. Passes up his practical work by currying dairy cows.

name: Reynard, Chas R.
comment: "But come, for England" One of the loyal sons of John Bull. Crossed the big pond to become proficient in the "Yankee" methods of treating all forms of quadrupeds. Noted for his ability to tell the ages of horses by their teeth. But when it comes to the final exams, "The Duke" is always found to be among the highest.

name: Rickey, Lacey F.
comment: "I meddle with no man's business but my own" "Rick" is a "horse" at turning out practical, readable Ag Journalism stories. Quits school every once in a while to go back to the farm.

name: Ringheim, Irene
comment: "A maiden never bold of spirit." Believes in taking things as they are, but would like a chance to vote against Phys. in H. Ec. course.

name: Rogers, W. L.
comment: "A contented spirit is the sweetness of existence" Clearly "Rog" has a mind of his own and uses it, too—sometimes. He refused to ride Parley's goat back and forth from town and now is known as a financier and economist.

name: Rudnick, Marie
comment: "When I have a subject on hand, I study profoundly" Marie came to Ames from Kansas Agricultural College. A shark if there ever was one. Conducts German caucuses in the library every noon.

name: Russell, Willard E.
comment: "This man toils, yet not too hard and is satisfied." Rusty came to us from the edge of the state. He studies hard and believes in "just one girl." These activities have deprived the debating teams of a decided acquisition, for he has much spouting ability.

name: Ryan, Ada Claire
comment: "Good nature and good sense must ever join." Only looks on the bright side of things. Pretty good friend of those from Brooklyn.

name: Scarborough, Hugh
comment: "Well, you darned old fool, you." "Hugh" claims to concentrate all of his fussing into the summertime. Always cheerful and full of fun—has a great admiration for Prof. Porter's "horse sense." Has athletic ambitions, too.

name: Schloeman, Henry O.
comment: "I was not born for courts or great affairs, I pay my debts and say my prayers." "Heinie" is a walking information bureau of baseball. Takes life very seriously, especially his college work. Intends to farm but doesn't believe in batching.

name: Schultz, Orville C.
comment: "Matrons flung gloves, ladies and maids their scarfs and handkerchiefs upon him." Instructs the preps. in the vagaries of chromosomes. Never hurt anyone's feelings in his life.

name: Seeds, Edward
comment: "A still small voice." It took this lad two years to break away from home ties but now has quite an ambition to fuss. He attributes a large share of it to his pompadour.

name: Seiler, Elmer
comment: "And when you come to know the man, you see quite easily. His bark is worse a dozen times than e'er his bite could be." Old man Seiler's son. He is particularly attached to the English department but still knows the ups and downs of a churn and can score butter forwards, backwards or in his sleep.

name: Ernstrom, Carl Y.
comment: "A man of actions and ideas, withal unassuming" Carl is always busy. Spends his spare time working for the A. E. and C. E. departments. He reports for the Student and also finds time to annex some fine grades to his credit. Fusses in extreme moderation.

name: Seymour, J. H.
comment: "There is no darkness but ignorance" "Dad" used to teach school in the good old-fashioned way until he heard of I. S. C. and Ag. education. His arguments with Dr. Cessna kept the girls awake in Psych. classes.

name: Shumway, Abigail
comment: "I would rather sit on a pumpkin, and have it all to myself than to be crowded on a velvet cushion" Conscientious and studious. Here for the purpose of getting an education, but cannot be called a "grind." Has a weak spot in her heart for S. U. I.

name: Simpson, Chas. O.
comment: "Of all mankind each loves himself the best." A lad of such light-mindedness that he was obliged to specialize in metallurgy. He believes that one must take medicine so that the doctors can live. He made his start at I. S. C. with the '14's but decided to hold over a year.

name: Sims, Marjorie
comment: "As we journey through life let us live by the way." Doesn't believe in worrying but always comes out ahead. Chief aide-de-camp to the modern language department.

name: Smith, Allan M.
comment: "Your face looks honest." A whole-hearted member of our class, who believes in doing well whatever he begins. Some stock judge.

name: Smith, Cecil
comment: "Yea, like a steam engine in trousers was he" "Smooth" is one of the original slippery boys— the hardest man to tackle on the team, and always full of the good old A-M-E-S.

name: Smith, F. R.
comment: "Right welcome, sir! Ere we depart we'll share a bounteous time" "Smithie" was one of the smallpox victims. A good fellow who works hard. Often entertains company from Des Moines.

name: Snyder, Lloyd B.
comment: "Books are fatal" A quiet fellow who is more bent on learning the best way to farm than on making a lot of noise in college.

name: Spencer, Harold
nicknames: A countenance more in sorrow than in anger
comment: A sad-eyed young man, who seems to be loaded down with worry. Once managed a dairy farm. Came to Ames to get some science along with practice.

name: Stacy, B. F.
nicknames: Like slow punk burns, but gets there just the same
comment: The man that coached Dolly Dimple in her run for a world's record. Always ready to lend a hand and never afraid of work. The future proprietor of "Stacy Brothers' Dairy Farm."

name: Steen, Clara
comment: "She doeth the little things that most of us leave undone"Enters into everything with enthusiasm and never lets it waver until the task is finished. Always willing to help the other fellow.

name: Storey, Katie Marie
comment: "Wisely and slow; they stumble that run fast." Never gets excited. Her true worth lies under the surface. When asked what was her worst habit, said, "I don't know."

name: Strandberg, Fred W.
comment: "Speech is silver, but silence is golden." "Stran" lives up to this proverb. When he does break the spell, the occasion is to be remembered. Fusses to some extent but devotes most of his energy to his mining pursuits.

name: Stuckenbruck, Harold C.
comment: "The fruit derived from labor is the sweetest of pleasure." Although carrying a heavy schedule, "Stucky" finds time to engage in other activities. Although a bachelor in the literary society world, yet from present indications "Stucky" will never find himself in that lonely state.

name: Summers, Glenn H.
comment: "A youth he was of quiet ways" "Bugs" has just as much trouble passing up Zoo as anybody. Hails from the land of tall cornstalks and full milk pails. Glenn was never known to study, flunk, or fuss. His ability is proportional to his height.

name: Summers, R. J.
clubs: Captain I. S. C. Cadet Corps
comment: "Wisdom personified, sawed off, and many times stretched" Parley's right-hand man. Aspires to be a pullman conductor. Rings the chimes in his spare minutes. "Knows not, and knows not that he knows not."

name: Sunderland, H. H.
comment: "A blythe heart makes a blooming visage" A strong believer in a warm welcome for the preps. Was once a Mechanical, but changed to Ag. Engineering so he could work nearer the Home Economics building.

name: Sunderlin, Howard L.
comment: "The pen is mightier than the sword" Has his eye on Uncle Henry Watterson's job and the Gridiron Club. In the meantime, he is teaching the "Ags." the peculiarities of B. subtilis.

name: Swan, J. H.
comment: "A man died in a hurry once" A lanky fellow that takes life very seriously. Can tell wonderful stories of northern Iowa.

name: Swaney, Gilmore D.
comment: "Assume a virtue if you have it not" "Gil" has a circle of privileged friends who can tell you all his good and bad qualities. We are unable to say certainly whether he has any or not.

name: Swift, Harvey M.
comment: "Salute ye the stranger within your gates." A new man at Ames but nevertheless dispenses the I.S.C. spirit in a loud tone of voice. Has lots of fussing ability.

name: Taff, Lillian C.
comment: "So womanly, so benign, and so meek." Works hard but will, at any time, take time to forget it.

name: Thomas, J. Fred
comment: "The rule of my life is to make business a pleasure and pleasure a business." "Fritz" is one of the hustlers of the dairy department. Looks forward to a lot of good hard work after college days and is preparing for it now.

name: Thompson, Stephen C.
comment: "'Tis not deep as a river but who would have it deep." A thin little fellow who has the welfare of the Juniors at heart. Is a loyal booster.

name: Thorson, Theo.
comment: "Knows a lot but can't think of it." "Thors" doesn't make mistakes intentionally. He is a good, practical man that gets results in an unassuming way. The man with the four-story haircut.

name: Thurman, A. G.
comment: "I said it; it must be true." A man with a lot of ability when it comes to pushing the hot air. Is a practical farmer and a good extension man.

name: Foenies, T. A.
comment: "Quiet, modest and useful" "Ted" was never known to study too hard, but he is always ready to help anyone who needs help. His favorite diversion after a pleasant evening spent downtown is to walk back to the college—because the last car has left.

name: Tomlinson, Paul
comment: "Who? Me? Why, I'm the college jester." "Tommy" is running over with sharp wit, and is not stingy about handing it out in large packages. A combination of politician, athlete, and student rarely found.

name: Truax, Earl R.
comment: A native of the Hawkeye state. Passes up campaign by working for the Chautauqua Circuit during the summer months. Is seriously considering locating in New Mexico. Considers a typewriter one of the requirements for all students during their college course.

name: Stephenson, A. R.
comment: "He was not merely a chip of the old block but the old block itself." "Little Stev" is absolutely impartial as to his role in life's work. He is your "friend for keeps" or your best enemy, just so something keeps "doing."

name: Stevenson, R. S.
comment: "I want what I want when I want it." "Big Stev" says this is a queer world. "Now, Swift wants to run the college, Rath the Kappa Delta Pledges, but personally I'd rather 'Ona Barber.'"

name: Stewart, F. Lee
comment: "Pure friendship is something which men of an inferior intellect can never taste." A generous mind and the cultivation of good books and men has made "Stew" a capable and worthy fellow.

name: True, R. H.
comment: "Officious, innocent, sincere" His ambition would make him president of the United States. Sincere fellow who works hard and talks much.

name: Valdez, J.
comment: "An ounce of pluck is worth a ton of luck" One of our friends from other lands. A man who has done much in spite of his handicap in English.

name: Van Anda, John L.
comment: "A For e'en the vanquished he would argue still" Can talk more than any other man in school. Once informed a class in animal husbandry that the Shetland Islands were located just off the coast of Africa.

name: Vickerstaff, S. G.
comment: "Ye gods, I am a man after mine own heart" "Vic" is a hard worker, whether it be in athletics or as the college laundry magnate, collecting bills past due. Has tried a little of everything since he has been in college.

name: Walker, Van B.
comment: "A youth to fortune and to fame unknown" "Van" was a '14 but stayed out a year to build the Keokuk dam and other engineering projects. Quiet and reserved. Tends to his own business and saws wood.

name: Ward, Lottie E.
comment: Likes fun any time, anywhere, and in any form. Especially fond of wading. (Proved by certain non-securable kodak pictures.)

name: Warden, Robt. P.
comment: "Ward wants but little, here below— But he wants that little long." Abraham Lincoln once said, "A man's legs should be long enough to reach from his body to the ground. 'Red's' are at least that long, and who can but envy a man that lives in realms of his own."

name: Watson, Besse
comment: "She seemed a thing that could not feel, The touch of earthly years." Too busy (?) to enter into college activities. Inclined to let dates interfere with study hours, but manages to get there in the end.

name: Wenger, Joe
comment: "I am a regular heart smasher." Joe intends to be a dairyman if the fair sex will permit. He is a good student from necessity rather than desire. Knows Des Moines well enough to find his way around in the dark.

name: Wentworth, Marion
comment: "Be always merry as you can, For no one delights in a sorrowful man." Is a good mixer and has a "stand-in" with all departments. Without her, what would we do? If you want to get her fussed, say "Love among the roses."

name: Westley, Roy O.
comment: "Begone, my cares! I throw you to the winds." All the girls envy "Wes's" pink complexion and curly hair. Roy is a loyal band man whenever a varsity game is on. He came to Ames to get his name on the corn-judging trophy.

name: White, Mary
comment: "There is weight behind her words." Even thinks Zoo might be worse. Known to have spent her holidays in Ames waiting for a Christmas box from home (?). Clever in originating and impersonating highly amusing characters.

name: Whitney, O. R.
comment: "We never broke a darn thing." "Eli" knows enough football to win his "A" next year if he will get out and do it. A rough-houser and a jolly companion.

name: Wiley, Chas. E.
comment: "I meddle with no man's business but my own." "Doc" has been the wonder of the Ags, since he received a grade of ninety-seven in his freshman year from the "Phys" department. A constant fusser, but manages to keep it quiet.

name: Willey, Florence
comment: "Queenly of spirit, big of heart, We cannot choose but love her." "Flo" is noted for her delectable dinners, and her grace and dignity as a hostess. Nothing funny ever escapes her big brown eyes; "the world is happier because of her."

name: Wilson, Edwin J.
comment: "On their own merits modest men are dumb." A regular race horse on the cinder track. "Ted" is usually modest and unassuming. Is well liked where known. A man who tends to his own business.

name: Wilson, Emma Lou
comment: "She is not little, though she is small of size." Believes in having a good time but can really work if necessary. The kind you can't help but like.

name: Wilson, Annie Faye
comment: "They that love mirth let them heartily drink, 'Tis the only receipt to make sorrow sink." Faye is noted for her abrupt and rapid speech and for her good hearty laugh. Always loyal to her class and everything connected with the institution. A good "mixer" and a stanch friend.

name: Wilson, Harrison B.
comment: "Some men were born for great things" Has a thatch of short-clipped hair, of a decided blond color with lots of gray matter underneath. "Wilse" is an enthusiastic booster for all I. S. C.

name: Wind, Hortense E.
comment: "Neither too young to be wise, nor too old to be careful" Helps to encourage chemical minds of the preps. A good student and a good friend.

name: Winter, Leon A.
comment: "His strength of mind is exercise, not rest" He is from Sumner, "Nuff sed." "Leon" studies and fusses hard when necessary. Frequently finds it unnecessary. Blows his own horn (in the band) and finds his chief amusement along musical lines. Has a large stock of good nature and is not as wintry as he looks on paper.

name: Wood, P. E.
comment: "There's nothing like being used to a thing." One of the cinder-path friends. A quiet fellow with a pink complexion and an ability to dress extremely up to date.

name: Woodroffe, H. B.
comment: "For let 'em be clumsy, or let 'em be quick, young or ancient, I care not a feather." W-o-o-d-i-e is fond of hunting at night. Has been known to stay up late just to scare a cat. Is one of the quiet ones who takes life easy.

name: Yockey, Rex
comment: "Night after night He sat and bleared his eyes with books." "Red" finds all work, flat, stale, and unprofitable. Still he "shines" in every class, a bright fellow in every sense of the word.

name: York, Ethel
comment: "She is pretty to walk with, And witty to talk with, And pleasant, too, to think on."Another one who switched over to I. S. C. It's impossible to say the nice things we all think of Ethel. Went to Cornell two years first.

name: Zimmer, Leah R.
comment: "To live, to love, to be glad, give and be given." Has many admirers, but one in particular. A good one to have in a lively bunch.

name: Ahrens, Ida
comment: Ida is an all-around good girl, whose good nature, lovable and unselfish disposition make her a friend of both students and faculty.

name: Anderson, J. L.
comment: Has a dry wit all his own. Always stops in Des Moines on his way home. Look for his picture later in the book.

name: Anderson, J. P.
comment: Never fusses the college girls. Probably engaged. Works hard when necessary. Will some day help to make I. S. C. famous.

name: Anderson, Lancelot S.
comment: A quiet, hard-working, business-like chap. We expect great things of "Andy."

name: Anderson, Walter L.
comment: "Andy" has a personal magnetism that is as quiet as it is attractive. He is a hard worker, yet seems to take life easy.

name: Arthur, Ira W.
comment: Believes that the pen is mightier than the sword, and that flowing ink is more effective than hot air. Always appears to be in good humor.

name: Atwood, Guy H.
comment: "Ata" is the kind of a fellow who does not make much noise, but gets there just the same. Is a diligent student and a first-class agronomist.

name: Axthelm, Edward E.
comment: A good engineer and athlete. No slouch at fussing, either.

name: Aydlette, H. P.
comment: "Doc" believes in getting as much sleep as possible during poultry lectures. Never lacks something to say.

name: Baie, Emma A.
comment: There is no limit to a woman's possibilities. Business first, then pleasure. Says she can see now why a popular girl can't do such good college work.

name: Bakewell, Adela
comment: Her name reminds one of pies and other luscious edibles. That may be the reason she's a H. Ec.

name: Barker, Frank F.
comment: "Runk" is one of the biggest hearted men on the campus. He enjoys a big roughhouse next only to going to "Grinnell." Is a good judge of camels.

name: Barker, Leland H.
comment: "Molly" was christened at the Sophomore Class Play, and the name has stuck. Expects everyone to be as peppy as he is.

name: Barnhart, Sadie
comment: "Sade" is a quiet girl, and very studious. A good friend to have.

name: Bass, Helen
comment: Stays at Margaret Hall to assist the Madame in watching over the preps. A conscientious worker, but in for a good time. Interested in Y. W. work.

name: Baustian, Alfred A.
comment: Left wheel horse of the front rank of the Dutch Band. Gets up ambition enough, along with an equal amount of love for his big brass, to polish it before every trip. He's a good engineer, too.

name: Baxter, Howard A.
comment: Does fussing enough while at home on vacations to last him for the whole college year. Delights in using his dry wit on his friends and his dry batteries on his enemies.

name: Bean, Ward
comment: Attended Iowa State Teachers' College two years. Is hard pushed to choose between mining engineering and industrial science.

name: Beach, Walker C.
comment: "Rex" believes there are many benefits to be derived from a moustache. Is quiet and peaceable at all times, except when one mentions Zoo. 8 to him.

name: Becker, Joseph Philip
comment: Joe has lately (or has he been so inclined always) taken to continuous fussing. Has inclinations toward good tobacco and roughhousing.

name: Becker, Raymond B.
comment: A good student, and carries on lots of outside work. He will be found either in the soils department or on the lookout for a H. Ec. girl in Ag. Hall. Look for his wedding picture elsewhere.

name: Benson, Donald J.
comment: "Ben" likes nothing better than pounding a hole in the head of the big drum when Ames scores on Iowa. Believes in co-education.

name: Bentley, Russell
comment: Proprietor of the Sophomore Hotel. Should have no trouble in passing up Campustry, as he is in with the chaperon.

name: Bilderback, Charles M.
comment: Entertained the boys in Soils lab. by boxing with "Dad" Smith and breaking "Dad's" dessicator. Is a rising track man.

name: Birlingmair, Robert H.
comment: A thorough student. Has won out against odds that would have daunted many a stronger man. Skillful in devising excuses for visiting Indianola.

name: Bird, Albert R.
comment: "Birdie" is a big, husky, genial chap who is interested in both the practical and the clerical side of Animal Husbandry.

name: Blakeslee, Ralph O.
comment: A hard-working chap who works when he works, and works when he plays. Aspired to be an orator until Miss Shattuck interrupted him while delivering his masterpiece.

name: Bliss, Fred G.
comment: Thinks he missed his calling when he took the Dairy course. Imports in preference to local brands.

name: Boileau, Harl
comment: Says that if a diploma depended on fussing he never would finish I.S.C. Will have to get a proxy to propose for him.

name: Booker, George F.
comment: Someone has characterized him as a "queer little genius." A friendship with this quiet enthusiast is something to be prized.

name: Bourland, C. Curtice
comment: "Dock" has more grit on the track than when in the presence of ladies. A man who will make his mark.

name: Boltz, Joe
comment: He "bolts" at every opportunity. Needs an "official persuader" to keep him moving. If Joe is missing, you'll find him asleep on one of the tables in second floor steam and gas lab.

name: Brady, R. A.
comment: A quiet fellow who believes in looking out for No. 1. Does not believe in fussing. Is always on hand to usher for chapel.

name: Brasted, Dea J.
comment: A quiet, good fellow with lots of pep who stayed at the Y. M. C. A. for the first two years. Nobody enjoys a good joke more than "Brace."

name: Brekke, Julia E.
comment: Jay is a shark, but doesn't know it. Gets up at four in the morning to study Zoo.

name: Brown, Andrew J.
comment: Inclined to be underestimated as to pep because of his quiet personality.

name: Brown, Eugenia
comment: One of the advanced class of consistent fussers. Should be classified in the Poultry House. Course. A dandy fine girl and liked by all who know her.

name: Brownell, Fred
comment: One of Minnesota's best products, noted for his light hair and sunny temper. Attended Grinnell until he got tired of it.

name: Bruner, D. L.
comment: Never run after a woman or Parley's Goat. After another term of Public Speaking will be an efficient salesman of farm machinery.

name: Buehler, Charles L.
comment: The official baseball guide for '15. If hot air was wind, "Chuck" would be a cyclone. It is reported he got a con in campus lab.

name: Buffington, Estella
comment: Estella is a very blond lady; always cheerful, with a smile for everyone. Has to write out a joke in order to see the point.

name: Burhans, N. C.
comment: Learned all he does not know about farming at Burlington. His dignified air and high-brow language take well with the ladies.

name: Burnquist, Eleanor E.
comment: Always has a smile on her face. A good talker and a better bluffer. Believes in having a good time.

name: Burrus, Norman
comment: "Slim" was Ames' long, lean high-jumper in 1914. Won first in the State Meet. Got his pep for the Missouri Valley Meet with his keen eyesight the night before, "so they say."

name: Burrill, Percy
comment: A good student and a comer in educational lines. Attended Grinnell one year. Percy is his name, but he has failed to pass up even one semester's campus lab.

name: Bussey, Ella L.
comment: Ella is from the land of high winds and prairie dogs. A loyal booster for I. S. C., but has a weak spot for Yankton. Thinks seriously of investing in a peanut roaster.

name: Butler, A. I.
comment: Knows something about everything. Appreciates a good story and can tell a better one.

name: Cameron, Ada E.
comment: Ada is popular with men and girls alike, in spite of her green eyes. Studies hard, and is frightened every time she is called on to recite. Says she can't bluff. A brilliant student in Home Economics.

name: Cambre, Robert G.
comment: Is much inclined to be funny once in a while, but will hardly make a mistake in discarding the clown's cap and paint for the farmer's tan.

name: Capper, Howard M.
comment: Laundry magnate. Is liked by all the co-eds as well as by the boys. Always smiles and is happy. Will make a name for himself some day.

name: Carson, Gladys S.
comment: Attended college at Tarkio, Mo., one year. "Carson is her name, Single is her station; Happy is the little man Who makes the alteration."

name: Carhart, A. H.
comment: In Hort., as in everything else Arthur tackles, he hits the line low and hard. Is a fine member of the glee club, band and orchestra.

name: Cash, H. W.
comment: A quiet, peaceful fellow who does his work well. Not much of a fusser, but won't get a "con" in it.

name: Cassidy, Hugh O.
comment: He is as care-free as any of the foresters. Believes in having all there is in today, and then doing the same for tomorrow.

name: Caywood, G. C.
comment: Came to I. S. C. because of love for the Phys. department.

name: Clark, Fred
comment: A native son of Cornell, who escaped the hardship of trying to get an education there by coming here, to Ames.

name: Clarke, Ruth Harriet
comment: Attended Parsons College one year. Came to I. S. C. to take Home Economics. "Ruthie" came to us and we're mighty glad to have her here. A lively little girl, and liked by all her friends.

name: Clayton, J. W.
comment: Likes Summer School experiences, because they are short but sweet.

name: Collins, Chauncey M.
comment: Chauncey won his fame at Missouri by winning the 100, 220, and beating out the Tigers' crack relay man.

name: Collins, D. R.
comment: A man the Bomb Board could not have done without. Like Edison, he never stops work until he has finished. Rumored that he fusses a Lott.

name: Conrad, Harold N.
comment: Little, but mighty. Prof. Porter's favorite, in class and out. He likes Hydraulics because he can sleep some. A good fellow and a good engineer.

name: Cook, J. Neel
comment: Has all the eccentricities of a genius—he elected an extra hour of Phys.! An authority on the slide rule.

name: Cordiner, R. P.
comment: Steady, and Scotch. One always knows where to find "Bob." Does his best everywhere.

name: Cornell, Harvey H.
comment: Musician, athlete, usher and good fellow, and proficient in all. One of the kind we all like.

name: Covey, Ellis
comment: Loves his motorcycle when it runs well and he is dressed for a fast ride.

name: Cox, Eva
comment: "Coxy" would make a very good boss, but knows how to work, too. Has a wide reputation for being a chatterbox.

name: Cramer, Earnest Faville
comment: "Dad" was chosen on the all-state basketball team. His long shots always put Ames in the lead. His chief aim in life is to beat Iowa, and to become a professor.

name: Crane, Harlan B.
comment: Sings for the Pi Phis in the early morning. A hard worker who is always in for a good time.

name: Crittenden, Cecile
comment: If Cecile had been a better pal of Raymond's, she might have gone home earlier spring vacation. She believes in relieving laboratory work with fun any time. Is Lois' rival.

name: Crouse, Floyd L.
comment: Although the busiest man on the campus, yet seems to have time to attend to all of his multitudinous duties. Well liked by all.

name: Curtiss, Ruth
comment: Is reported to have the keys to certain rooms in Central. Is very proud of the advantages she acquired during her year at Randolph-Macon. Has a reputation for being good looking and well dressed.

name: Davis, Bernice
comment: A good grade-getter, an excellent fasser, and an authority on letter writing. For testimonials, see H. D., Chicago.

name: Davis, Clarence J.
comment: Davy's smile is an introduction and an expression the same as "welcome to our city." Never overexerts himself, but gets there.

name: Davis, Willis H.
comment: "Bill" is not only an all-around good athlete, but a good student. Farming in South Dakota appeals to him more than anything else just now.

name: Dean, James W. M.
comment: While very young, "Jimmie" and work had a falling-out, and despite the efforts of the faculty, he is still at odds with it. Manages to "get by," however.

name: De Bar, Harold J.
comment: Large but graceful. Enjoys asking questions, and very capable in that capacity. He knows everybody's business as well as his own. A good worker.

name: Delaney, F. J.
comment: Specializes on wedding announcements. Got to first base in football, but makes his home runs in social events.

name: Devine, Mary Helen
comment: Another inconsistent person. Says she is a man-hater, but is rumored to be engaged. A very conscientious worker. Asks lots of questions.

name: Dexter, Willis E.
comment: Has a faculty for passing up work without being classified in it. Came here because tuition was too high to stay longer at University of Wisconsin.

name: De Wet, Louis R.
comment: Attended Elsenburg Ag. College two years. Looks a little wild, but is really mild when thoroughly known. Says some parts of the United States haven't much more civilization than parts of South Africa.

name: Dewey, Grace
comment: Grace is a "shark" in everything, even Zoo. Almost fusses the Zoo. prof. when she asks him a question! Especially interested in church work, which gives her a fine excuse to call up the men.

name: Diehl, Grace V.
comment: Grace spends most of her time in Botany laboratories of various sorts, when she doesn't go fussing. Generous, jolly and a lover of a good time.

name: Dool, Lawrence E.
comment: Most outstanding characteristic is that he is a "good feeler." "Red" always has a smile for everyone. He may even be caught grinning at Margaret Hall.

name: Drake, Wilbur
comment: He once offered himself to be stretched at a mass meeting before a Drake game. Is here for all that he can learn at college.

name: Drain, Harry E.
comment: It's "funny" Harry is not called "Red." Perhaps it's because everyone likes him too well.

name: Dunlap, Howard P.
comment: "Pack" is an easy-going sort of a fellow who doesn't worry much about anything but the ladies. Is especially noted for his "line of talk" among the fair sex.

name: Eales, Howard C.
clubs: Athletic Editor I. S. C. Student '12-'13
comment: The busiest man in school. Always figuring up some scheme whereby he can beat the other fellow to it.

name: Earl, Lorne T.
comment: Earl is the real ladies' man. Fussing is his third given name, and he does his level best to live up to it. Constantly fears that he will get the mumps on the other side.

name: Eddy, Lilian R.
comment: Lilian never caused any real excitement. Always generous and ready to help the other fellow.

name: Edgar, Mary T.
comment: A very dignified looking personage, but sometimes looks are very deceiving. A very good student, and works hard.

name: Edwards, Lois A.
comment: Lois can certainly play the cornet. A very conscientious student. Assists in Botany lab.

name: Ekstrand, Walter L.
comment: A fellow who would rather dance than eat. He is also quite fond of the ladies and is never so happy as when he is with them.

name: Eldridge, Joe M.
comment: A busy man. Rides a motorcycle. Can see only one girl on the campus.

name: Engberg, Russell
comment: It is not safe to say too much about those over you in office. Russ has taken an active part in many college activities, but it has been said that he will have a hard job passing up campus lab.

name: Englar, Daniel S.
comment: An exception to the rule. The only quiet Junior Civil. He thinks that the rest of the Civils make enough noise for him.

name: English, Ruth G.
comment: Ruth is a living interrogation point, but usually finds out what she wants to know. Thoroughly enjoys a juicy bit of scandal.

name: Englund, Carl V.
comment: Carl is sore distressed since the opening of the war. Doesn't believe in work when he can get out of it.

name: Ender, L. R.
clubs: Contributing Editor I. S. C. student
comment: L. R. is perfectly willing to work in Zoo lab, if he can have a big chew of "Star." Is the official reporter for the Register and Leader, which accounts for the popularity of that paper at Ames.

name: Evans, Valney L.
comment: "I train my hair in the way it should go, and ever I know it, 'twas gone." Aspires to be a world renowned traveler.

name: Eves, Jay Parvin
comment: Passed up "prep" drill by attending Quaker Church during his Freshman year. "J. P." is one of the coming A. H. men of our class. He is a smooth politician and a good student.

name: Fahnestock, Ludlow S.
comment: Believes in passing up "prep" Chem. with smiles. "Slim" seems to have most of his "troubles" in Watertown, S. D., but you would never think it from his actions around here.

name: Fitch, Ernest L.
comment: "Rusty" started his fussing career at Le Mars, but he did not follow it up very strongly. Spends his summers selling maps. Sang a solo on Sunset Rock the second evening he was in Ames.

name: Flint, Pauline A.
comment: A living chatterbox if there ever was one, but a hard worker and a sensible thinker nevertheless. Fond of ghostly pranks on Hallowe'en.

name: Forman, Mary M.
comment: "Merry" is noted for her inexhaustible conversational powers and ability for seeing a joke. A good sport and a good friend.

name: Forest, Ida Gertrude
comment: Prof. Dadisman thought she was an ex-school teacher. She says she is afraid she will have to teach some day if she doesn't get married. Doesn't let the "ice wanted" sign stay up week-ends.

name: Fox, Lloyd W.
comment: "Doc" bosses the gym gang around with a loud tone of voice. Is glad he will finish school before the prohibition law takes effect. Looks forward to the Vet. Banquet with great anticipations.

name: Fraseur, G. L.
comment: A peppy member of the squad which follows the football team through thick and thin, pocketbook or not.

name: Freshour, Ralph J.
comment: The man from whom "Tris" Speaker got his name. Industrious, almost studious, and quiet—at times.

name: Galloway, J. Carleton
comment: "Jack" enjoyed Organic Chem. so well that he took an encore in it. The Cafeteria could not run if he should quit school. Takes a keen interest in Seminar.

name: Gaylord, Bennie E.
comment: Bennie never is flurried, but he gets there just the same. Some sweet girl will find him some day.

name: Geasey, Sylvester
comment: He would rather sing than eat. Among other things that he is fond of are dark colors, particularly "Brown."

name: Geisler, Max
comment: Max is the man whom the musicians about the college go to when they want a job playing for a dance. Has been accused of sending Ag. Club money to the Germans.

name: Gibbs, R. C.
comment: "Gibbie" has a complexion that all the girls envy. Good fellow and student, in spite of his winsome ways.

name: Gibson, Vernon C.
comment: An ardent supporter of the prohibition league, and a constant fuser. "Gibbie" was born to be a teacher, and is going to make a mark in that profession.

name: Glidden, Warren C.
comment: Works for the Document Room. Is engaged, and likes Hort. S. Is always happy.

name: Gordon, William A.
comment: One of the busiest men on the campus. He finds time to occasionally go to classes, when he is not writing newspaper items for the Student.

name: Goede, M. H.
comment: In Goede we have a quiet, good student, the kind that is well liked, especially by the girls.

name: Graham, Lorraine
comment: Lorraine has a quiet disposition, a strong character, and more friends than she can count. Puts up an umbrella when she thinks she hears rats.

name: Gray, Lulu
comment: "Louie" believes in saying exactly what she thinks, but still keeps her friends. A true "Scotty," but sometimes scraps with her Scotch prof. Says she thinks "he's smart."

name: Gregg, W. S.
comment: Has no whiskers, but shaves four times a week. Never fusses unless he is paid for it. Hunted all over the judging pavilions for Bot. 61 when he was a prep.

name: Griffith, Ora M.
comment: "Neatness" is her middle name. A conscientious worker, but believes in having a good time. Especially interested in the "movies."

name: Grimes, Hazel A.
comment: Hazel is one of the consistent workers and gets good grades as a result. Her real work lies under the surface.

name: Gude, A. J.
comment: More pep behind those dreamy eyes than you'd think for. Called "skeeter" because of the place from which he came.

name: Hamilton, Riley A.
comment: "Plunder" is a hard worker and attains results, too, for he is one of the best grade getters in his class.

name: Hamlin, Herbert M.
comment: Attended Carleton College. A man who has lots of ability and uses part of it. Is especially good at digging up stories for the Student.

name: Handy, Harry Carlton
comment: Harry is a hard worker and a good grade getter. Told an A. H. prof. that Berkshire are bacon hogs.

name: Hardy, Gladys N.
comment: A demure little lassie, but passes up campus lab each semester with an honor. A good friend and a good student.

name: Harrington, Mary Elizabeth
comment: An industrious, zealous worker, true blue. Passed up campus lab when a prep and is now working for a master's degree.

name: Harris, Margaret B.
comment: "Tall and very fair is she," a good student, generous, unselfish. Very fond of tennis at five a.m. Fusses in moderation.

name: Harris, Nell
comment: The committee could find absolutely no scandal about her. Always tends to her own business.

name: Hartmann, Anna E.
comment: Quite a match-maker, always trying to get dates for Seniors. If you want to "fuss" her, quote "I love you, Van, I love you." Very quiet. Studies when she doesn't fuss.

name: Harvey, Nelle
comment: The other girls are trying hard to break her of chewing her fingers. Is strong for the honor system in classes and exams. Used to have an interest in a variety store at home.

name: Hawk, Lura Alice
comment: Her jollying makes Chem. and Soils labs endurable for the instructors and other students. No one can ever get ahead of her. Takes more and harder laboratory work than anyone, just because it's fun.

name: Hawks, Joseph W.
comment: Joe was, according to his own admission, single till he met Hazel. He is taking Science, and is much interested in Girls' Hockey. We hope he will be successful in combining these two principal interests.

name: Hawthorne, Fred W.
comment: Nathaniel's little brother. Was a mechanical engineer as long as his agricultural inclinations would allow. A husky chap for his size. Drives a "Ford" and has an inclination towards "Forestry."

name: Hayward, E. G.
comment: A good fellow and business man. Climbed to the top of the new smoke stack last summer, in company with a member of the fairer sex, just to obtain a view.

name: Heise, Linda
comment: Linda told the professor she was "mislaid on the way to class" once. Her greatest interest is her hope chest. You can't find out from her whether or not she intends to be back next year.

name: Heise, R. W.
comment: Does a lot of thinking, but doesn't say much. Holds cross country record between campus and Zumicalt. Always wears perfume to class.

name: Hendriks, John Albert
comment: "Windy's" nickname sure fits him. Got another fellow's girl because of a similarity of names, and kept her because of his good looks (?).

name: Henderson, Divida H.
comment: A quiet, inoffensive maiden who fusses in moderation and studies some, too. Usually gets by with her work.

name: Herner, Eleonora
comment: Eleonora never has moods. Studies hard and never grows discouraged. Is a loyal and sincere friend.

name: Hewitt, Leland H.
comment: Has lost interest in campus lab. at Ames since his Freshman year. Thinks more interest should be taken in minor sports.

name: Hilleary, Harry
comment: Harry enjoys Junior Phys. lab. on Saturday morning because the girls have a class across the hall. It is said that he went fussing three times in one week; bad for Harry. He is a fine fellow to know, and a good engineer.

name: Hibben, Robert C.
comment: The new laundry magnate. "Bob" is ambitious and studious. He never laughs—a smile is his elastic limit.

name: Hodgson, J. O.
comment: "Hodge" clings to the cinder path all winter; even Jack Frost, after biting both ears, couldn't drive him off. One of the coming Dairy judges of our class.

name: Hoffman, O. A.
comment: Left this institution, but not for practical experience. Assisted in wiring the college Christmas tree. Has passed up his course in campus lab.

name: Holbrook, Russell Merten
comment: What he don't know about fussing isn't worth while. A likable fellow who never worries.

name: Hollister, E. H.
comment: "Holly" has some queer ideas, but he certainly can run, sometimes. Shinnies poles and strings wires in the summer time.

name: Hopkins, P. F.
comment: "Hop" has lots of common sense, and knows how to put it into practice. Perhaps that's the reason he got married before coming to I. S. C.

name: Hoover, Bert E.
comment: Quiet, studious—the kind of a friend one likes to make. A good, all-around man.

name: Houghton, Earle
comment: A tall, handsome gentleman with the air of one who knows what he is about. Took Science so that he could associate with students of every department, especially H. Ec.

name: Hoyt, Harold A.
comment: Hoyt is a quiet fellow for the most part, but has the pep and punch to make his way and win friends.

name: Hultz, Fred S.
comment: It is rumored that this "happy-go-lucky" chap will join the ranks of the Benedicts next June. Used to come to Zoo. Lectures early and entertained the boys on the piano. Was "in the money" in the moustache contest.

name: Hutton, Ethel M.
comment: Attended Coe for two years, but came to I. S. C. for the privilege of taking Chemistry. A chatterbox at home, but elsewhere you would never guess it.

name: Huxtable, G. S.
comment: Hux has strewn the world with broken hearts all the way from Le Mars, Ia., to Pasadena, Cal. Is always talking about "riding a free horse." Doubtless the expression started because of excessive livery bills.

name: Hall, Harry
comment: This Ag. Engineer puts in his spare time at Tilden's Store, as a side line. An easy-going fellow who always gets along well.

name: Ineck, C. H.
comment: Stayed out a couple of years to be a forest ranger. A good, live member.

name: Jackson, Millard F.
comment: Small of stature, but has a big heart. A booster for everything that deserves boosting. Is a moderate fasser.

name: Jensen, Lucile M.
comment: Went to Cedar Falls two years, but the men were too scarce there, so decided to come to Ames.

name: Johnson, Ava L.
comment: "Johnny" believes in getting at the bottom of things. Is a living question mark in the classroom. Always has a cheerful word and a smile. An all-around good girl and a good student.

name: John, Edward T.
comment: Makes more tackles than any other man on the team. A powerful defensive football player, one who always backs up his teammate. Success to next year's Cyclone leader.

name: Johnson, Cora B.
comment: Won a prize last summer getting subscriptions for a leading market paper—her picture appeared daily during the contest. Wears a forester's pin, but says she has had it so long she never thinks about it.

name: Johnson, W. DeWeese
comment: Was contemplating changing his course to Ag. Eng., for he has his eye on a position in the department. Spends his spare moments in the gym trying to keep down his weight.

name: Johnson, J. Clarke
comment: One year at Hastings College. A son of Nebraska who is a delightful fusser. Always happy, a good scout, companionable, "Lionnie" is a fellow worth knowing.

name: Johnston, J. Carl
comment: One of the good, big fellows of the school and an expert tailor. "Johnse" is a good worker and likes a good rough house.

name: Jones, B. B.
comment: A good judge of fruit, and believes that the proof of the fruit is in the eating.

name: Jones, Edward P.
comment: Jones is the 'big noise' of the Junior Horts. Boosts for the Pacific coast continually, but can see good in other places; hence his presence here.

name: Josselyn, H. E.
comment: "Joss" was on the cross country team in 1911, but decided to wait and graduate with the '16's. He takes a live part in all college activities.

name: Juzek, Harry J.
comment: Of such a retiring nature that Doc Murphy didn't know him after having him in class a year. Has a failing for "flicker" shows and peanuts. Visits Sioux City regularly. Should get married.

name: Karr, Arthur I.
comment: "Mother" is here for what he can get out of college. Showed that he is a comer by exhibiting some prize-winning samples at the corn show.

name: Kelly, Raymond C.
comment: A wizard for work. Became popular by passing out free cigars, made in Davenport. Came to Ames to learn how to farm.

name: Kellogg, Lee A.
comment: Started his college career at Oregon, but came to Ames to find himself a wife. "Killy" always looks on the bright side of life, and is welcomed wherever he goes.

name: Kerrigan, Frank R.
comment: One of the peppiest men on the baseball team. Always fighting—doesn't know what it is to give up.

name: Keating, Zoa M.
comment: Looks out for No. 1. Zoa came to Ames after a year at Iowa, and has a very good reason for staying here. Is superior to conventionalities.

name: Kimball, Earl H.
comment: "E. H." has never worked off his "con" in campus lab. He don't let it worry him at all, either. He is a good student and a fine fellow to all who know him.

name: Kinnick, Nile C.
clubs: President-elect of Y. M. C. A. Cabinet
comment: One of the biggest little men in college. Believes in politics, and has pledged himself on the governor's side.

name: Kintzley, Harriet May
comment: And besides all this Harriet lives in the country and walks back and forth every day. So small you wouldn't think she would care about Camels.

name: Kirk, Ivan M.
comment: Official spieler for the Junior E. E.'s. Anyone desiring information concerning any subject, ask Ivan M. Kirk. The only one of its kind in existence.

name: Kirk, Ralph H.
comment: Seems to enjoy being sick now and then in order to be able to spend a week or two in "the city on the hill." A good fellow and a good worker.

name: Kivell, Wayne Allen
comment: "Pinky" always works at top speed. Has a dry wit, which probably accounts for the fact that he intends to sell bricks when he graduates.

name: Knupp, Rachel
comment: Very clever and dependable, though they do say she forgets. Has an especial aversion to alarms, and would like to find some insect powder guaranteed to kill the ticks—in the clock.

name: Krantz, Earl B.
comment: "Hatch" spent two years at Oregon State College, but is not sorry for making the change. Is an authority on "Knock-Hock" of horses.

name: Kriege, Caroline C.
comment: Carrie is a staunch believer in the powers of conversation. From all reports she would enjoy living on a farm, dairy preferred.

name: La Crosse, Howard C.
comment: Tends the college sheep, engineers a rough house, slings hash, tames the preps or tells a long story, all with equal facility. Famous for his warwhoop. A rolling stone, but manages to gather a little moss.

name: Lamson, Charles S.
comment: He may be short in size, but he is long in brains. Dancing and high grades are his specialty. "Cy" has a good "line," but few people know it.

name: Landman, S. J.
comment: An engineer by profession and choice. His love for the Phys. department varies inversely as the square of time. A natural shark along engineering lines.

name: Langdon, Edgar
comment: When spring comes, "Tang" always asks someone how it feels to be in love. Would make a good "ag." because he is such a good judge of "corn."

name: Laubenfels, C. R.
comment: Persists in going about the campus with a scrawny appendage on his upper lip. Is about as much at home in the water as on land.

name: Leffler, Robert W.
comment: A care-free, likable chap who studies occasionally. Doesn't believe in making himself conspicuous.

name: Lemen, Beth
comment: Has decided opinions of her own, and is not afraid of expressing them, in the class room or elsewhere. Doesn't care to be serenaded by cats.

name: Levi, Alexander James
comment: "Solomon" is some public speaker. Is a loyal booster for Dubuque. Wore his "prep" suit to dinner the first week at I. S. C. A charter member of Madero's Frat.

name: Lewison, Edward K.
comment: A good engineer, a good sport, and a good friend of everyone who knows him. Is very fond of schoolma'ams.

name: Li, Young Bing
comment: When things quieted down in China, Young Bing came to I. S. C. He will put Ames pep in Chinese Horticulture upon his return to China.

name: Lilliard, J. Myrl
comment: Myrl came to Ames from Parsons, and has since become a Chem. shark and an addition to the Scrub Faculty. A very serious-minded and conscientious person. Loves to repeat scandal.

name: Lovelace, O. H.
comment: "Lovey" is strong on interfraternity baseball and Vet. 56. A past master with a furnace, and hence strong with the "home-makers."

name: Tregilgus, Chester V.
comment: A "bloody Vet." Made his "T" look like an "L" when he wrote his name in Quade's book and hence his place among the Juniors.

name: Longworth, Harral A.
comment: "Nick" has an eye for business, and enters into most of the college activities. A strong aid to the debating team, and has plenty of confidence.

name: Lyford, Reid B.
comment: Where there's "Life" there's hope. Reid doesn't say much, but he keeps pegging away. Moved to Ames so that he'd always have the car handy.

name: Maakestad, W. T.
clubs: Varsity Track and Cross Country '14 and '15
comment: To get his name pronounced correctly has been his only difficulty. "Mae" is a plugger and is sure to get there with the best of them in cross country or elsewhere.

name: Manhardt, Clara
comment: Clara is one of the Famous Knoxville Quartet. Has a charm which fascinated the "Suffragette." Isn't slow about passing up campus lab.

name: Mason, Clair G.
comment: Clair started his college life at Cornell, but decided that Ames was the proper place for him. Has a life job at the state fair announcing the prize winners.

name: Matson, T. F.
comment: Matty is slow, but he generally gets there. Has a different pair of rubbers for each and every one of Iowa's 57 varieties of weather.

name: McCarthy, Carrell C.
comment: Look out for Motorcycle Mac! A member of the Cass Lake Brass Band. Takes Forestry because of the joys of summer camp.

name: McCausland, Robert J.
comment: "Red" sings in the Glee Club and draws the attention of the audience by stumbling on the steps. Is specializing in Chem.

name: McClung, V. W.
comment: Chief of the T.O.C.’s at Ames; also a strong supporter of the "fussers’ union."

name: McCoy, Marjorie
comment: "Margie" doesn’t believe in worrying, and always comes out all right in the end. Would rather dance than eat, which is saying a lot.

name: McCrae, Floyd E.
comment: "Mac" is somewhat given to journalism, and is there when it comes to soliciting and writing ads, for the Student. Has a way of his own that makes him successful as a public speaker.

name: McCurdy, R. E.
comment: "Mac" has had lots of good experience in practical work, and takes lots of interest in everything. We are looking for Mac to make good in football next fall.

name: McDonald, C. E.
comment: "Dopy" is a good mixer, and believes in getting as much out of life as possible. Is a booster for Cedar Rapids society. Is an authority on sports.

name: McElroy, R. C.
comment: "If my nose wasn’t so long, I know the girls would all 'fall' for me." At any rate, "Mac" seems to have the dates. His ambition is to get married.

name: McKinley, Harold L.
comment: "Mac" is liked by all. He has the fight and persistence to "go thru" and "make good."

name: McNee, Lawrence
comment: "A little fussing now and then is relished by even the best-looking men." Takes machine designing so well that he is still at it.

name: McNutt, Phil
comment: "Happy-go-lucky Phil" is a fellow to meet on dreary days, as wherever he goes, with him goes a bit of quaint humor and a happy smile.

name: McTavish, H. G.
comment: Not as "absholootly" Scotch as might be supposed. A wrecker of peaceful quietness and guitars.

name: Meeker, Homer C.
comment: A big, silent fellow who goes about tending to his own business unless he comes in contact with someone with whom he disagrees. Then he will argue.

name: Merrick, C. I.
comment: Merrick goes to Marshalltown now and then to a good show. A great fellow with the girls, and they seem to enjoy his company.

name: Merten, E. L.
comment: Attended Morningside College once. Has been seen fussing once. Thinks A. E. is the only course worth while. Is the proposed chief for a date-making bureau for I. S. C.

name: Meeteer, Ellwood J.
comment: Now making extensive investigations concerning "walnut." Long, graceful, with slightly wavy brown hair, he is beautiful to behold. Booster for East Orange.

name: Middleton, H. E.
comment: Is no ladies' man, but has been known to fuss. Not satisfied with taking both Ag. and Engineering in one course, he is taking special work in Ag. Education.

name: Mildensten, E. J.
comment: Hard to tell whether he is from Cedar Rapids or Clinton. Used to teach school until they found him out. Is interested in the Y. W. C. A. It is rumored that the Federal League is after him.

name: Miller, Richard C.
comment: Thinks a good deal of Minnesota, but prefers Ames as a place to go to school. Is a constant worker, and is bound to stay on top.

name: Minteer, C. C.
comment: "Percy" started out at Gates Academy in Nebraska, but came to Ames to learn the science of farming. Interested in numerous activities, and makes good in all of them.

name: Moffat, Alex R.
comment: His greatest beauty is his style of wearing his hair, and his brown eyes. Is not too sedate.

name: Moore, Eugene Ralph
comment: Moore came to us from the sunny South. He is a good worker and a jolly fellow; always has a good word for everybody.

name: Moore, George G.
comment: "G. G." is one of the quiet ones who, without worry or flurry, go peacefully about their business, and get there, without a brass band accompaniment. Very likable when known.

name: Moore, Glen.
comment: A good, conscientious, hard-working man who is bound to make a name for himself.

name: Morris, R. D.
comment: R. D. has an unconquerable aversion to studying. Likes to go auto riding with Foster. Is a first-class forester and sticks close to his course.

name: Moyer, Ralph H.
comment: Ralph is another man who deserted the '15s in order to join our ranks. It is said that he has been conditioned in campus lab., but we do not believe it.

name: Mueller, Paul M.
comment: Studies M.E. when not thinking of her. Can sleep equally well in Mechanics class or in Des Moines street cars.

name: McMullin, R. S.
comment: "Mac" plays some game of tennis. He likes to sell books in Dakota and to ride Bronhoer incidentally. A good student.

name: Mulky, Mina M.
comment: So diplomatic she can manage three men at one time, when one is in Maine. Doesn't hurt herself studying. Sings bass in the Knoxville Quartette.

name: Munger, George H.
comment: George is one of the most consistent fussers on the campus. Spent his last summer's vacation collecting bugs and lemons for the Botany Department. An expert in stacking rooms and tailoring. Goes clear to town for his lit. society work.

name: Noble, David A.
comment: Holds the cross-country record from the college orchard to the north woods. Fights every minute when in a game. Is a promising stock judge.

name: Noble, Mont C.
comment: An enthusiastic advocate of the honor system at all times and in all places. Hangs onto his ideas with the utmost courage and persistence.

name: Nye, Maurine
comment: A tall goddess—belongs to the Pi Phi Engaged Girl Club—and to the Old Maid Club temporarily. Doesn't like to go to school.

name: Obye, Charles H.
comment: Is majoring in Lemen culture. Spends his summers hunting bugs for the entomology department. Is a smooth proposition, and gets by with a lot of work.

name: Okey, M. Robert
comment: "Bob" has a hard time getting central to understand that he wants RED 532. Is the champion batter of the "Stove League." Is noted for his cool head when in the pitcher's box.

name: Parks, Laura
comment: Attended I. S. T. C. two years. Here is a nice, quiet girl who tends to her own affairs. She once won fame on account of her beauty lotion—apply peanut butter each night on retiring. Ask her about it.

name: Parsons, Leslie L.
comment: "Les" came from Grinnell to Ames because he wanted to learn to farm. You can't get him peered—he's always in a jolly mood.

name: Patterson, C. C.
comment: "Pat" is a jolly good fellow who has lots of ability. Has taken special work in Janitor Engineering, Campustry, and Dairy.

name: Patterson, Ralph E.
comment: "Pat" has a leaning toward the honors of war. Sure to be a sergeant if we go to war.

name: Patty, Ralph L.
comment: "Pat" is a first-class student and he knows how to play tennis. Has a characteristic drawl, by which you would know him in the dark.

name: Pearson, Arthur R.
comment: Worked so hard that he had to drop out a semester to let the rest of the class catch up. Has made himself indispensable over at Margaret Hall.

name: Peek, Alice Marion
comment: Has wonderful dimples, which are always in evidence. Says her whole family is engaged.

name: Penningroth, Edward W.
comment: Three of his brothers graduated at S.U.I. He decided to come to Ames and get a little "hoss sense." Likes to ring the Victory Bell on all occasions.

name: Perkins, Juanita
comment: "Perkie" came to I.S.C. to take H.Ec., and according to all appearances will practice the art very soon in a "cottage built for two." To her charms may be added a sweet disposition.

name: Pervier, Norville C.
comment: One of the kind worth knowing. A good musician and student.

name: Petersen, R. W.
clubs: Winner of Soutter Grain Judging Medal
Second for Sophomore Grain Judging Medal
comment: Believes in having things systematized. Will have a four years' course card-indexed when he graduates. Has a lovely pink and white complexion and blushes easily, especially when he visits the Pi Phi House.

name: Plagge, Homer H.
comment: "Comisky" is a fellow you like in spite of yourself. Not pushing himself forward, he has become a true friend to many in the last three years.

name: Plagge, Newton O.
comment: Pep enthusiast. Ready for anything with real enthusiasm connected with it. Famous for his ride in a spring wagon, which, like all famous things, was not premeditated.

name: Pownall, Paul C.
comment: A consistent worker, who habitually receives honor grades. He doesn't fuss much here at school, but does very well while at home in the summer.

name: Rath, H. Earl
comment: A sincere, hard-working chap who goes into everything he undertakes with unbounded zeal. Liked by all who know him best.

name: Rath, Lois Myrtle
comment: A good student, strong for athletics, successful in all her attempts, yet doesn't mind when things go "punk." Her escorts think her enthusiastic rooting much more interesting than the game itself.

name: Rawlings, J. B.
comment: Came to I. S. C. because here is the best Engineering school in Iowa. Has almost switched to "Forestry" within the last year, but expects to graduate double E.

name: Reed, Merle K.
comment: Is strongly opposed to woman's suffrage. It is said he was seriously considering going to the war when he returned from Christmas vacation. Is one of Costello's star draftsmen.

name: Reynolds, A. W.
comment: "Bert" inherited his love for dairying from his father. Wanted the best there was in dairying and came to Ames to get his start.

name: Riedesel, P. Wayne
comment: Ried experimented at Drake three years before he got his bearings and decided to take C. E. at I. S. C. If the ducklings have any more like him, pray send them up.

name: Riemenschneider, Alma
comment: Attended Cornell two years. Doesn't like to be called "Dutch." Has opinions of her own, and stands by them. A sister to the Adelantes.

name: Richardson, H. R.
comment: "Rich" fusses occasionally, so that he won't get out of practice. Will make a first-class farmer if his dad does not make a Ford salesman of him.

name: Richardson, Lewis E.
comment: Is as good as he is tall. Never says much, but always means what he says.

name: Roberts, Harold P.
comment: Never "fussed" in his life. A good fellow when you become acquainted with him.

name: Roberts, T. H.
comment: Tom might easily make good on the stage as a wit and humorist of the louder type. A good fellow.

name: Rodgers, Helen
comment: Helen is a jolly, curly-headed lassie. She says she is a man-hater, but from all appearances this may be doubted.

name: Rogers, Bruce A.
comment: At college for knowledge. A serious sort of a lad, a good student, and well liked.

name: Ross, Merle
comment: A girl quite indispensable to her friends. Very dependable, and always in for a good time. Especially fond of "kidding" the Zoo.

name: Rossing, Tedmar M.
comment: By his own admission, "Grandma" is exceptionally clever as a heart smasher. Attends classes regularly except on examination days. Bids fair to become a wonderful and speedy technician.

name: Rue, Nelson B.
comment: Nels has joined the rank of the Married Men and the "back to the farm" movement at one and the same time. He couldn't "Waite" until graduation.

name: Ruesink, Edward
comment: Attended Drake one year. Quiet and hardworking. He can sleep very soundly during a recitation, waking up abruptly to give correct answers to questions asked by the profs.

name: Rush, I. L.
comment: Likes Machine Design so he can practice hitting the cuspidor. A fine fellow to know, and a good student.

name: Rumbaugh, W. R.
clubs: Business Manager of the Ames Forester
comment: King of the Newsboys. Rum is on the way to becoming a big factor in our national forest administration. Persists in smoking out on the campus.

name: Ryan, Madge Clair
comment: Irish as the day is long, but partial to the Dutch, especially "Steins." Has curly hair in damp weather. Ask her when shoe polish is the greatest economy.

name: Scott, C. C.
comment: Scotty is preparing to teach school, and also in the home, if the reports from Cornell College are correct. Is a good student and should succeed in both places.

name: Scott, Milton H.
comment: A man of high ideals and high attainments. "Scottie" has a wonderful faculty for making friends and keeping them. Finished his course in campustry in his prep year.

name: Searle, Wellington
clubs: Sac City Institute and Two Year Ag.
comment: A quiet, conscientious fellow with a determination to succeed. If industry spells success, he will not spell down.

name: Seder, Merlin L.
comment: Merlin has been trying to form a Janitors' Union ever since he started firing the furnace. Is a regular "war horse" on the cross country course.

name: Shideler, Charles J.
comment: "Whitey" won high honor among the students by breaking up classes the day before the Iowa game. One of the best natured fellows in school, noted for his white hair and aggressiveness.

name: Skott, Hans E.
comment: A good Dane. One of his first acts when he came to Ames was to enter Alumni Hall via the East Entrance. Among other useful things learned at I.S.C., Hans has become more at ease with the young ladies, "stern" of them in particular.

name: Slingerland, Don E.
comment: Long, lean and hungry looking, believes that Climax is a first aid to passing up A.H. Wears a smile from head to foot, a good worker and a good talker.

name: Smillie, E. W.
comment: Jack has rare ability as a standing high-jumper. Can tell great stories about life in the "wild and woolly West." Believes that Iowa is a good place for a student to live.

name: Smith, Andrew N.
comment: Made himself famous by mistaking one of Prof. Kinney's maps of Iowa for the map of the U.S. Has solved the high cost of pasturing live stock by fusing a grass widow. Likes to have the parlor alone. Is pet of all the profs.

name: Smith, Earl W.
comment: Earl holds the highest grades of all the Junior Engineers. Is a quiet, unassuming person who is liked wherever he goes. Has never been known to be idle.

name: Smith, Fred Dean
comment: "Dutch" left Cedar Falls because there were too many girls there to suit him. Generous and considerate, even to smoking on the roof of the porch when cigar smoke was offensive to his roommate.

name: Smith, Glenn M.
comment: G. M. is one of the dependables. Is enthusiastic about the future of all Horticulture, and about Eagle Grove.

name: Smith, John B.
comment: J. B. is a consistent jasser. He loves the ladies. A very live talker when in the presence of fellows. Paralyzed when in the presence of the fairer sex.

name: Squire, E. G.
comment: A capable fellow who has worked his way through school and yet taken part in many college activities. About to be married.

name: Steigerwalt, Frank
comment: Stayed out a couple of years to get some practical experience. A jolly good fellow, who keeps all the friends he makes.

name: Stewart, Margaret B.
comment: A nice girl, but will be "Swift" some day unless signs fail. Is a jolly good sport, always in for a good time.

name: Stewart, Olive Mae
comment: A thorough student who is blessed with a brilliant mind. Olive is a good sport and a true friend. Likes "Doctor's" care and attention.

name: Stoddard, Erling
comment: Erling is a good student in spite of himself. Grades all things evil from the Phys. department up. Has love affairs, yet somehow keeps good natured.

name: Stokes, R. R.
comment: Goldie does not let the fact that he is working his way through school interfere with his having a good time. He and his bass horn are prominent features of the band.

name: Stover, Fern H.
comment: Believes in having a good time at Summer School if she doesn't have time to go to class. Starts to school at eight o'clock and rides around to H. Ec. on the car.

name: Stuewe, Erich F.
comment: The man with the winning smile. Hails from the town that Pabst made famous. Erich does things, but never tells about it.

name: Surring, R. E.
