comment: This promising young Vet. goes to Boone to trade overcoats. Goes sightseeing in Des Moines in a taxicab. Is to become the secretary of a matrimonial bureau after graduation.

name: Susong, Homer D.
comment: "Susie" is an ardent lover of a good time, and has a mania for starting things. Swears off "fussing" every Monday morning.

name: Swiney, John D.
comment: "Chick" is known all over the Missouri Valley as "Ames' fighting forward." He led the Cyclone basketball team through a victorious season. When he is not to be found at Chem. Hall, call Black 489.

name: Symonds, Harold H.
comment: Dates have such an attraction for "Syme" that he once tried to pick up a couple of his own club mates, one dark spring night. He isn't very talkative, but certainly likes to express himself on the piano.

name: Syverud, A. O.
comment: Came all the way from South Dakota to teach the preps how to drill. Loves to stretch preps and to play interclub baseball.

name: Taintor, Elmer J.
comment: A clear-cut type of man whose chief delight is in pulling down high grades.

name: Talcott, James P.
comment: "Jim's" planning on finishing next year. He has about decided to start in at Lake Benton, Minn. Jim is a good athlete, but has had hard luck.

name: Tallman, J. Glen
comment: "Heavy" is considering changing to the landscape gardening course. Is a grade-getter in any subject he carries.

name: Taylor, Ferne
comment: Her originality, wit, and conversational persistence make people work to keep up with her. Forgets that other people may be sensitive, too. Always says, "O! My heart!"

name: Temple, William M.
comment: "Bill" has been trying for a job as half-miler on the track team for two years and will undoubtedly be rewarded for his efforts. Is a sure shot with an army rifle.

name: Thiel, William L.
comment: "Bill" got started smoking celebrating St. Patrick's day and has not been able to quit. Stays until the last man has gone home each vacation, so as to see that each carries home some bricks.

name: Thomas, Merton G.
comment: Dick started with the '15 class, but stayed out one year in order to stay with a good bunch. Is a good student, and a comer in agricultural lines.

name: Thornburg, Herbert W.
comment: Likes to waste the chalk and to break the erasers in hydraulics class. Watch him when he smiles.

name: Tillie, Robert S.
comment: Tillie brought fame upon himself by smelling the rifles to discover the man who shot off a cartridge on the campus at the Battle of Prep Run. Is a booster for the Muscatine Fire Department.

name: Tippie, John M.
comment: Jack may be quiet, but he can always be depended upon when needed. Got his academic training at Highland Park, and lost his heart in the effort.

name: Tonsfeldt, Alma
comment: Alma is a good, hard worker, a good student, and a constant fuser. Very generous and dependable. Is looking forward to a pleasant life on an up-to-date dairy farm.

name: Torblaa, Erling M.
comment: This red-headed gent believes in smoking up when he is out for a time, pulls cigars out of every pocket. Started studying for a preacher, but all theologians discouraged him.

name: Turpin, H. W.
comment: "Turps" starts wearing the lapels of his cap down over his ears with the first frost, and keeps them down until the trees blossom. Is an authority on sheep.

name: Tuttle, Otis H.
comment: He saved the baseball team by finding "Mildy," the southpaw twirler. "Ote" is a jolly good fellow, and his ability is only outdone by his dry jokes.

name: Tucker, Fred Raymond
comment: A graduate of Cornell College who has decided to obtain a real education.

name: Ufford, Glen R.
comment: It is said that "Speedy" has already signed a contract to teach in the Phys. department. Spends his summers railroading on the Ft. Dodge, Des Moines and Southern. Is a booster for a smokeless campus.

name: Uhl, Edwin J.
comment: One of the most powerful line plungers in the West. Unanimously chosen all-state fullback. In addition to being a football man, he is rapidly becoming a ladies' man.

name: Van Anda, Carmi Housten
comment: Was John Evvards' apprentice for one year, and is now going to show the boys how to raise hogs on the Nebraska sand banks. Is a staunch believer in universal peace.

name: Van Fossen, John R.
comment: The lure of the big, red apple induced "Van" to leave the beaten track of a straight college training at Cornell College and come to Ames to get a closer acquaintance.

name: Van Vlack, Claud H.
comment: "Van" is loyal to Simpson and to Atlantic. He is so quiet the call to Atlantic keeps him in a constant turmoil here at Ames.

name: Veach, Claude
comment: "Red" is of a happy disposition, and one of his biggest and best characteristics is his quick smile.

name: Vorhes, C. A.
comment: Can store away more ice cream than any three ordinary men. Would have been an A No. 1 track man if they could have found shoes large enough.

name: Walker, Dessie
comment: Always the same and always happy. The kind of girl who is liked by all those who know her.

name: Walter, Elmer V.
comment: "Doc" is the kind of a man who will be heard of after he leaves college. He became famous selling aluminum cooking utensils.

name: Warden, A. W.
comment: "High" is the smaller one of the Wardens. A star on the basketball floor. Believes thoroughly in disciplining the preps.

name: Wallace, James J.
comment: "Jim" is specializing in chickens. Is determined to discover a life partner before leaving I. S. C.

name: Watson, M. R.
comment: "Boone" is so full of tricks that his friends say he is "ornery." Always conscientious, and a good student.

name: Watkins, Florence
comment: We can't imagine where she got her nickname. Owner of the best cooking notebook in the Junior class. We wonder if she could make "Johnny's Cake."

name: Wenholz, Alfred M.
comment: Is very antagonistic towards a bookworm. Took the two-year Ag. course and liked Ames so well that he decided to take a four-year course.

name: Whitney, Verne E.
comment: "Whit" says he came to I.S.C. to get acquainted with the girls at the Bentley House. Doesn't believe in letting class work interfere with his business.

name: Whitson, Jay
comment: Notorious for his arguments with the Profs. Talks as long as anybody will listen. A sincere man, with high and worthy aims.

name: Whittemore, Osgood J.
comment: A happy-go-lucky fellow. Claims that the Ceramics department has a greater percentage of fussers than any other department in the college. Whit is sure doing his best to keep up the record.

name: Winchester, Harry B.
comment: "Chesty" spent a good share of last summer perfecting a new method of using a husking pin. Still gets his "daily" from Missouri and strongly believes in seven days of "grace" in each week.

name: Wingerson, Vera
comment: A very quiet but lovable miss—not especially interested in school work. Says she would rather be at home keeping house. It sounds suspicious.

name: Wilcox, Fred A.
comment: Fred is an A No. 1 student, and will make his mark in the world. Has been leading the life of a bachelor for the last few months, but is going to finish strong.

name: Wilkinson, H. E.
comment: "Wilk" believes in always having a "Mary" time. Is one of the good students in the institution. Is a comer in the newspaper business.

name: Williams, Harold J.
comment: Is a great basketball enthusiast, for he hails from the town made famous by Ziggz and Zim. Is singing his way through school.

name: Wilson, Ellanor
comment: Never worries and never hurries. As nice as she is pretty. Always has a train of admirers. Oh, those big, blue eyes!

name: Wilson, Eva Rose
comment: "Little Evah" says she's the Alpha Delt goat when it comes to "draying" things to school. Gets her work, but likes to have a good time. Had a course in "sleight of hand" last year.

name: Wilson, Helen
comment: Has not been in the school long enough to create a sensation. Will probably be heard from soon, however.

name: Wilson, Ray S.
clubs: Vice-President-elect of Y. M. C. A.
comment: One of the best plunging halfbacks that Ames ever had. Hits the line like a bullet, and always keeps fighting.

name: Woodroffe, Clara
comment: A very enthusiastic camp-fire worker. Generous and kind-hearted. She always does more than her share of lab. work.

name: Woodworth, Robert M.
comment: Didn't do well growing a moustache. Stringy decided that the class of '16 was more desirable than that of '15. He feels perfectly at home in the presence of ladies.

name: Woolley, John C.
comment: "Prof." says he will never go to Des Moines again on a motorcycle unless he is manipulating the thing himself. Chief occupation in life is minding his own business and running the wheels off a "Hupmobile."

name: Wolf, Paul M.
comment: A native of the Buckeye state, who, after finishing a course at Miami "U.," decided to learn how to farm. An excellent student.

name: Workman, Nora E.
comment: Nora has a style all her own, noted for her sarcasm. Is thinking seriously of making carpentry her vocation.

name: Wyckoff, Marjorie May
comment: Got lots of practical ideas for future use from "The House." Is doubly a sister to Maury!

name: Weise, Raymond J.
comment: A natural diplomat. The friend of every student on the campus. Stayed out one semester to get some practical experience.

name: Yungclas, James A.
comment: Jim evidently believes in concentration, for he gets all his recreation, eats his meals, and does all his worshiping at the same place and at the same time.

name: Young, Ellsworth
comment: Sells books for Hermann Knapp at the book store. Has the qualities of a good usher.

name: Young, Marie D.
comment: A girl with a great big heart, always willing to do things for her friends. Liked by all who know her. Attended Rockford College, Ill., one year.

name: Benge, Berenice
comment: A steady worker who has always a cheerful word to say to all her friends.

name: Dawson, Richard Ancil
comment: Quiet and unassuming, but makes every word count. Has become so efficient in Home Economics that he doesn't intend to get married. Attended Drake two years.

name: Dunnigan, Lenora
comment: Stayed out a semester to recuperate from the brilliant social season at Ames. Seems to like Farmers.

name: Lovelace, H. Houston
comment: Aspires to be a baseball pitcher. "Shorty" always looks on the bright side of life. Has a smile for everyone.

name: Myers, Bert
comment: "Shorty" is always in for a good time, and generally gets it. Spends his summers building concrete bridges and smashing the hearts of the country maidens.

name: Nichols, Harry E.
comment: "Nick" is a little cuss full of the right kind of fight. Took one semester off to see practical work. Reported to have fussed the boss's daughter.

name: Pearson, Earnest E.
comment: High point winner in the President's Trophy meet, 1914. Does not have much time for the barbers. Can snore bad enough in the morning to close the windows. He is a good, all-around track man and helped tie a knot in the Tiger's tail at Missouri last year.

name: Scurlock, Clarence P.
comment: His motto is, "Never start anything you can't finish." Is a hard worker, and knows a good joke when he hears one.

name: Shivers, E. D.
comment: A quiet, congenial fellow of the South, with all the good features of his own people combined with those of ours.

name: Stewart, Minnie H.
comment: "Ven you see him, you will know him." Light hair and blue eyes. A friend to everybody.

name: Taake, Margaret
comment: Tried two schools before she found the right one. Said to have been born under a lucky star, especially when playing cards.

name: Waggoner, Charles J.
comment: "Wag" took a certain girl to a dance once. He thought she was Devine, but everyone else knew better. A hard worker on the cinders.

name: Walker, Scott Allan
comment: "Scottie" came to Ames from Iowa City, where he received his B. A. degree. The best Iowa University has was not quite enough, so he came to Iowa State College to get the rest.

name: Zimmerman, John C.
comment: "Zim" is a bit musically inclined. The Welch Society voted him in on account of his violin. A very likable fellow.

name: Agne, Glen L.
comment: He lies and dreams of things to be. Agony is one of the olden time motor dodgers. He was a staunch advocate of the cinder path. Quiet and reserved, he seldom gets riotous except when the gas runs low in soils lab.

name: Amesbury, Henry Clyde
comment: Enthusiasm is the intoxication of earnestness. —Lamartine. Amy has chalked it on the slate that he'll be a great engineer. But those curly locks, twinkling brown eyes, and dimpled cheeks could never belong to a successful section boss. They are classic and should wander in the vales of romance. They will probably prove his undoing at a very tender age.

name: Anderson, Arthur Lyman
comment: Yea this man's brow, like to a tragic leaf foretells the nature of a tragic volume. —Shakespeare. Things taste better to Andy done slowly—doesn't like to catch cold rapidly. Bacillus Camericus—fiendii warmed him into electing Phys. IX last semester. Thereupon he became Phys. Andy's handy Andy in Photog. General supervisor of the Agronomy section in the summertime—he hoes the soybeans.

name: Allen, Shirley Walter
comment: His eye begets occasion for his wit; For every object that the one doth catch the other turns to a mirth-moving jest. —Shakespeare. A man with such a wealth of experiences that he converts Bomb Board deliberations into testimony meetings. Studied Greek at Simpson, but it never took hard on him. Always decides momentous questions by what our friend the lumberjack would say. His stay in the Minnesota forests last summer would have made a man out of him if he had only let nature have her way.

name: Archer, Dorothy Anna
comment: Always happy but easily excited is this little Miss Archer from Archer. Quite loyal to I.S.C., but is reported to be taking a Junior study (steady) at Grinnell.

name: Baker, H. Ream
comment: Bake leads a kind of pyrites existence at I.S.C. But the fault does not extend throughout the whole formation. The tunnelings of time will fetch up against many a pay streak in his nature.

name: Bakke, Arthur Laurence
comment: Is fitting himself to be the College Chaplain when that position opens. Can make the worse appear the better reason in the history room. Verily a liar—or a debater—is a terrible thing in a class of ladies. (See '03 Bomb for explanation of quotation.)

name: Beard, Vivian Dangerfield
comment: This man stepped out of the procession late one September afternoon of '05 and sat down to muse. Since then he has been busy delving into the musty volumes of the past for engineering honors—reports say he has torn out several of them. A pleasant lad, just a little too engrossed in a nook and a book.

name: Beaty, John
comment: "There goes the parson, illustrious spark."—Cowper. "Jawn" is a prophet and can see the sin of a profit very readily. Born to be a preacher or a life insurance agent. Has given a number of illustrated lectures on "The Beaty Library System" and on "Why Corn Pops." Also advance agent for the Beaty Milk Stool Mfg. Co. Says he just can't help liking the girls! No wonder!!!

name: Bek, Hugh E.
comment: "I profess not talking."—Shakespeare. Was musing on the "can-do-it" system one day when the interurban car drew nigh. Result—While confined to his room he gave to the world that matchless treatise, "If an irresistible force meet an immovable object." Although from the land of the Platte, Hugh E. thinks Charles City, Ia., is the only place to spend a vacation.

name: Belles, B. B.
comment: "But to the world nothing is so great as want of figure * * * * *."—Pope. After "rubbering" for weeks to ascertain the significance of the B. B., the Bomb Board decided to apply Buster Brown as the two most suitable epithets obtainable. Bells had an awful time learning to see into the transit until the Dean came along and showed him how to straddle his legs* more.

name: Bernick, Fritz
comment: "Laugh at all things. Great and small things."—Byron. Looks like he knew things—comes natural to him. Fritz was once taken for a Chem. instructor. This is the only time on record when his feelings were hurt. A good student, but can see fun—even in Phys. *Of the tripod.

name: Billedo, Mariano
comment: "Days of absence, I am weary, She I love is far away."—Rousseau. "Bill" likes America and I.S.C. first rate, but he can't help but dream a little of palm groves (?) across interminable seas: A quiet, hard worker.

name: Black, Elmer E.
comment: "I could have laugh'd but lack'd the time." Notwithstanding his name, Blackmer is one of the whitest Vets. It is a very grave question, however, whether his gentle disposition will ever allow him to become a good Doc.

name: Boardman, Lois Knight
comment: "Had sigh'd to many, though she loved but one." When quizzed as to her future prospects, "Boardy" is said to have answered, "My smile is my fortune, sir!" Hails from Nevada—wears the Nevada clan plaid—and has been accused of riding freight trains, and even draw wagons back and forth home. However, the Board as a body never gave much credit to the last clause of the report.

name: Bodwell, Ross Edward
comment: "The thing done avails,—not what is said about it."—Emerson. A man who works unostentatiously—surmounts obstacles and "bloweth it not." One of the commonality of men who will go out from I.S.C. unwept and unsung to make good in the world of industry.

name: Booth, James Francis
comment: "I envy the man overwhelmed with the weight of his own leisure."—Voltaire. James F. would like to know "what's in this grand life and high situation"? Boasts that he has never attended a social function of any sort or condition since he came to I.S.C. Is taking Freshman French as Research Work.

name: Boyd, Lee Robinson
comment: "I drink to the days that are." Lee is a bright-eyed lad with a "who gives a care" attitude. A good student of the sprinter type. Says: "Never do today what you can put off until tomorrow, for tomorrow, you may not have to do it." Believes in having his room well piped—bulldog arrangement preferred.

name: Broadie, Ray Wesley
comment: "He handles the truth in a careless manner." Steve is a believer in the "let it soak in" theory of education. Did athletics stunts for the '07s in their coltish days. Uses loose grammatical constructions; he seems to have forgotten the specific adjectives and exact verbs of English III.

name: Burkhart, Roy F.
comment: "Stolen sweets are best."—Colly Cibber. We might comment on this quotation, but we won't. Burky is fond of foraging, with a transit—says it increases one's field of operations so wonderfully. Major study—Baseball. Minor—English.

name: Burris, John Arthur
comment: "Popular glory is a perfect coquette."—Goldsmith. A man who is working away and making no dust about it. The Bomb Board were out with their little spy glasses looking for famous '09s when they happened to sight him stolidly at work. To their accosting "What Cheer, Jack?" he replies with characteristic Irish style, "Fame only comes after you're dead and I'm in no hurry for it."

name: Bush, Charles Randall
comment: "Canst thou thunder with a voice like him?"—Job XL:9. Instructor in Public Speaking: "Mr. Bush, your voice covers a multitude of sins." But he will probably recover, for as yet none of the advanced stages of moral decrepitude such as horse stealing, wife beating, and the like have been noted upon him. Has a good working acquaintance with the zoological department, a thing which he used singularly well in the College Day auction.

name: Bielenburg, Carl Frederick
comment: "Take him to develop, if you can."—Pope. A tall lad with curly hair and black eyes. Could pose as a second edition of Adonis, but he doesn't care. Passed up Chem. but is still celebrating by retaining much of its phraseology. The stunt that has made him famous, however, is his writing little "heart to heart" expressions on the back of his blue book to catch the eye of his instructor.

name: Campbell, Paul Caldwell
comment: "It is our actual work which determines our value."—Bancroft. Paul is a man that says nothing and little of that. Indeed, it was only by beating up the brush vigorously that the Bomb Board was able to scare him out into the open for a second or two. But he has one of Prof. Stanton's "think tanks" that is always tappable when he is called upon.

name: Carlisle, Campbell
comment: "No brush had touch'd his chin, or razor sheer." Jocko lives in the poetic valley of the Squaw where he manufactured herbariums commercially in his prep days. Much inclined toward the dark side. Knocks mightily on the management—hasn't learned to knock cheerfully yet. Would like to get out in the world and be great, but "dad won't let me." Earnest student.

name: Campbell, John Roy
comment: "A wit with dunces and a dunce with wits." J. R. will crack wise in spite of fuzz and fair weather. Claims to have a stand in with the Botany Department, but that can hardly be true. He is now in the employ of the State Pure Food Commission. Query: Is this the cause or the result of his being a radical Prohibitionist?

name: Carlson, Walter Roy
comment: "Men like bullets, go farthest when they are smoothest." —Richter Peter is a little inclined to be moody, but he is quite smooth about it. He has a mania for masticating the fabric—when it is made into Whites' Yucatan. Scene in C. E. recitation: "Give the dog some gum, Peter."

name: Carr, Elza B.
comment: "As game as he is good looking." Trolley is an improved edition of Nervy Nat. Nerve wins his races; nerve makes those end runs; nerve warmed him into Bohm Bauerk's smile—well might we exclaim with the psalmist, "Oh the nerve of some people's children!" But it takes nerve to be a thoroughbred.

name: Case, Harold Mortimer
comment: "What, keep a week away? Seven days and nights?" Casey is a Hawkeye by birth but early hied him off to live with Montgomery Ward. The lad is a budding horticulturist, a good man generally, but he has too much chicken-heartedness—he will persist in talking poultry.

name: Chappel, Milford Edward
comment: "There is scarcely any man who cannot persuade himself of his own merit."—Sewall. Chap hails from a river town where he used to be sub weather man for this part of Uncle Sam's domain. He frequently goes home over Sunday—this no doubt explains why storm centers usually culminate at I. S. C. on Monday. Claims no relation to Chappel of "Heart Throbs" fame, but shows a nasty quill in English.

name: Clarke, Perry Benjamin
comment: "I saw a man by some accounted wise."—Ellsworth. Cheer up P. B., don't sigh; You've flunked E. and M. I trow, But the Technique slough and Chem. LII. Are things of the long ago.— Cheer up P. B., don't sigh!

name: Clayton, Daniel W.
comment: "To sow a jangling noise of words unknown."—Milton. Fond of noting the impact of flying chalk. Was once caught paying attention in D. C. class, but he afterwards regretted. Clayton is a jolly, good fellow, enjoying life and doing his best to help it along—sometimes shoving a little too hard.

name: Cockfield, Joseph Henry
comment: "Silence does not always mean wisdom."—Coleridge. Cocky works hard at times—careful never to get caught at it. Long on social stunts—gathers 'em all in. As a steward he is miles ahead of any other—he claims to have learned how to dodge Hintz with the samples.

name: Collins, Edgar V.
comment: "Who gain'd no title, and who lost no friend."—Pope. He and Happy Hamilton know more about a gasoline engine than any other one man on the campus. After losing a couple of teeth cranking one, he says you should always speak to the critters when you go behind them.

name: Cooper, Clifford William
comment: "How my achievements mock me; I will go meet them."—Shakespeare. About the only college honor Red ever took was that of Motor Dodger before the days of the cinder path. Is reported to use too coarse a sieve when looking for opportunities. Always good-natured—never gets red-headed about anything.

name: Cowan, Lynn Freeman
comment: "Seeing the root of the matter is found in me."—Job 19:28. A whole-souled, free-hearted lad as "boisterous as a lover's bended knee." Has made a rep as a writer and leader of football rooter songs. We might josh Babe some easy enough but we are too tender-hearted after what he has received in times past.

name: Cox, Paul Ira Franklin
nicknames: O name forever sad, forever dear
comment: A long man with a lengthy nomenclatural appendage. His sad countenance and general languor are without doubt due to his having bad air when small. He is endeavoring to correct the blunder by assimilating large quantities of White's Yucatan.

name: Craig, Dan S.
clubs: Vice Pres. Jr. C. E. Society
comment: The smile that is child-like and bland.—Bret Harte. Computes when to go to dinner by the slide rule. He is the man who, when he slid past the finals, wanted to hang the '09 Bomb on a handy branch of the Phys. plant.

name: Crawford, Mathew Oliver
nicknames: Knock and the world knocks with me, Boost and I boost alone
comment: Mike has the makings for an artist—he handles a facile pen. If he could only learn to put a little happiness into his characters or at least to choose a sunny day in which to conceive them! A charter member of the Ruff Hanser's League.

name: Crawford, Nate N.
nicknames: Better be a sinner than a cast iron monkey or a plaster-Paris cat
comment: Evidently quite a windjammer else he could not manipulate that bass tuba so efficiently. Oh Ikey what a business! And such a joker yet. Likes his eating tobacco first rate. A man who is smashing out a career for himself—in A. H. furniture.

name: Crouse, Ralph Clinton
comment: Bachelor. "For thy sake tobacco, I would do anything but die." —Lamb. Here is a living example of what a college training can do for a man. R. C. has been twice or thrice taken for a preacher recently. Some vile wretch has said his hair is fuzzy but we deny it—it's curly. And that corrugated brow came from peering into a glass too frequently. A good kid, if he'd only fire the weed.

name: Cunningham, Albert Henry
comment: "Poor prattler how thou talkest!" Her majesty's ship, Challenger, sounded that awful void of words and when down 5297 fathoms the wire broke—evidently it's bottomless. Cummy turns off work if he is noisy about it. About the only thing he ever attempted and didn't make go was the class presidency, but that was altogether the fault of the "ring."

name: Darling, Eugene
comment: "Your absence of mind we have borne, till your presence of body has come to be called in question by it."—Lamb. His is a striking personality—you'll look twice when you see him once. Does not stack up very big as a fusser but down along the Des Moines, in the land of the White and Blue, a little lass is singing, "I'm So Fond-a Darling So True."

name: Davis, Joseph Walter
comment: "I trow that countenance cannot lie Whose thoughts are legible in the eye." Davy is the knight of the long stride on the track and in scholarship. "They'll have swift feet that follow." Takes public speaking honors in big hunks. Likes to sit on the back of his neck in Soils Class.

name: Davis, Harry Kimball
comment: "And weaponless himself, made arms ridiculous."—Milton. "Now it occurred to me just for instance." Bull has had adventures in his life. Passed muster for a Drake freshman last fall and was asked to get out and try for the football team. His good nature gives way under strain—the fellows say it was worth the trip to hear him cuss the Swedes in the Minnesota game last fall.

name: Davis, Grace
comment: "She quits the narrow path of sense for a dear ramble through impertinence."—Swift. "Davie" is a fluent speaker—in public and elsewhere. Scrub Faculty—scrubbed prep algebra. Will not finish with us, having left recently to take work at Chicago University. The paths and byways of the campus are already lonesome for Davie and—but we promised not to say anything about it.

name: Day, Georgia Elmira
comment: "Sweet are the pleasures that to verse belong."—Keats. George was recently made poet-laureate to the Hall. Acting chief of the M.H. Board of Directors while Mrs. K. was in Europe. Scrub faculty—she scours the mathematical minds of the preps. Query: How can she harmonize poetry and Math?

name: Dengler, Harold D.
comment: "Who thinks too little and who talks too much."—Dryden. He argues interminably and at times his language is preeminently picturesque. Was for several weeks a walking (?) testimony to the efficiency of ——'s Corn Salve. He is the supreme authority on blow holes—would be a pretty decent sort if he'd stop casting jokes and stories in green molds.

name: Dorman, Bertram Levere
comment: Comes to us from a bad boy's town but is proving a pretty decent sort in spite of it. Apparently, Fate didn't brand him with the genius stamp, but he goes slow and gets there by and by. He is quite sure that he will make good when he publishes his original plan to keep "carbuncles" from forming on piling.

name: Dyer, Ruth
comment: A jolly good-natured girl, but in instances of (dire) Dyer displeasure, those eyes flash fire. Although a Dyer, she's no quitter in any style you spell it. One of "that Nevada bunch."

name: Dragoun, Frank
comment: It is doubtful whether the folks would know Heinie now. When he came to us, he was just a little fellow about as high as pappy's knee—now they say he is in love. Never was a leader in "slip stick" antics, but he does excellent work behind the counter. Filden Bros. couldn't keep house long without him.

name: Eby, Valentine Vincent
comment: Pete is a quiet little fellow with just spunk enough left to ask questions. If he only had just a little better opinion of V. V. Eby, it would help some! Has dabbled in politics some—wherefore the quotation. But the G. O. P. will probably attend to that. V. V. Eby, Esq., Co. Surveyor, Jones Co., Iowa

name: Edwards, Lyman Oscar
comment: "Unless a man works he cannot find out what he is able to do."—Hamerton. Edwards is of the quiet sort, noted principally for his ability to keep out of the limelight and off the Dean's calling list. He is counting on making his big strike in the after-while when the conspicuous men of today are sorting rivets for the G. E. Co.

name: Ellis, W. V.
comment: "I have an exposition of sleep come upon me."—Shakespeare. One of the average students that never flunks—never stars. Got up early one morning, got himself married, and is now living the simple life. Extremely fond of napping in lectures.

name: Ewers, Ruth Bradley May
comment: "O who does know the bent of woman's fantasy?"—Spenser. The worst thing about this fair lady is her name—no, an unmitigable evil, for she can probably change it to yours. Starred in the Junior Trot Circus. Came dangerously near flunking Chem. once, but she spunked up and now she comes dangerously near being a shark.

name: Farmer, George Eddy
comment: "Yes, ladies and gentlemen, on the steps of the campanile a man may even get very close to his ideal."—Farmer. This man's ultra-decorous appearance gained for him the appellation, Deak—and to look at him, you'd really think he ought to sit in the A-men corner. And the Board prophesies he will, too, after the next Debate try-out. Has a knack for the culture courses that the unknowing call graft.

name: Farnsworth, Fordyce Barker
comment: Doc never became notorious in college—evidently spends too much time watching how the other fellow does it. Possessed of an easy-going drawl that is long on argument—would make a fine debater if he could just convince the other fellow.

name: Farnum, Eugenia Fae
comment: Her lively looks, a sprightly mind disclose.—Pope. To see her walking across the campus you'd think she was going to a fire-sale. Fae is our co-ed exponent of the strenuous life. Her energy has awed the Board into submission to the following: 1. She is not to be called modest, demure, little maid; 2. She is not to be called Teacher; 3. She is not to be called Irish.

name: Forman, I. F. W.
comment: Ye rigid ploughmen! bear in mind your labor is for future hours.—Harne. When asked the object of his college course Lee answered that he was fitting himself to become the President of the Iowa Corn Grower's Association. An upright Ag—six feet and one inch up—who believes in saying to your face what he wouldn't say in front of your back.

name: French, Franklin F.
comment: Bright as the sun her eyes the gazers strike And like the sun, they shine on all alike.—Pope. Has attended every class meeting except the joint meeting near the Quaker church, and it is not certainly known that she was not at that. If all women were as thorough and as noble politicians the men would be down and out! Would like to legislate against Phys in a G. and D. S. Course.

name: French, Leslie Roy
comment: "It is tranquil people who accomplish much." —Thoreau. French is a good fellow, quiet and industrious. The Board gouged around with their little spades for some time, and the only scandal they could unearth was the fact that he went to the reform school (S.U.I.) one year. P.S. It reformed him.

name: Fuchs, Osboe C.
comment: "Laughter—the cipher-key, wherewith we decipher the whole man!" —Carlyle. This man laughs like a good feeder. He believes thoroughly (1) in fussing as taught in the Business Course of Morning-glory College; (2) in Short Horn Math. Classes; and (3) in the Ag. Department of the A.H. Course.

name: Gamrath, Carl
comment: "Be checked for silence, but never taxed for speech." —Shakespeare. Gam's early life was spent in a meat-market. Doubtless the love of gore instilled into his early years explains his affinity for Vet. Tells the Animal Husbandry men how to cut out Anatomy. A certain '00 co-ed says, "His hair ain't red, neither." He will probably be a great meat inspector when he sees this.

name: Garner, Della May
comment: "So vain is the belief that the sequestered path has fewest flowers." —Doubleday. A quiet, unassuming exponent of the gospel of hard work. "Oh, he's only a cousin of mine."

name: Gillette, Millie
comment: "My days are swifter than a weaver's shuttle."—Job VII:6. Says the beautiful days were all made for her use—the bad ones, for abuse. Was one of the English O instructors when that course was given at Margaret Hall. Acting judge at the dismemberment of the Prep pennant last fall. The bigger the risk, the better the game for her—but there's many a worse that she.

name: Gilmore, William Jones
comment: "A lusty reveler was he."— Bill is the lad who changed from Agriculture to the man's course. Charter member of Engineering Rough House League. Chief construction engineer of the Newton and Nowhere, summer '07. Went to chapel once but set 'em up to the crowd afterward. "Dunno" why he was instrumental in sending congratulations to John Berg.

name: Godfrey, George W.
comment: "Animals are such agreeable friends."—George Eliot. Used to be cat catcher for the Cornell College Zoological Department. Picking, getting short, he came to I. S. C. and became acting superintendent of Bill Rowe's department. His wise cracks in chemistry got his name up alongside Benny's. Now he's on the high road to be Agricultural Chemist. Would break up housekeeping if he got a grade below 93.

name: Gordon, Bert Earl
comment: "We rarely repent of speaking little."—Bruyère. He thinks much, works more, but, lest the world should find out the full extent of each, he says but little. Nothing in his student days has acted skittish with him except chemistry—but he and Benny were able, by skillful driving, to keep the brute in the beaten course. Helped to herd "preps" last term but found it exceedingly strenuous labor.

name: Marshall, Louis Graham
comment: "A merrier man, within the limit of becoming mirth I never spent an hour's talk withal."—Shakespeare. Always jolly and good-natured. Half his living consists in the opportunity to josh someone, whence his satanic nickname. Louie comes from the land where the mountains and sheep herders flourish mightily—he is thoroughly in love with both (?) A student from the drop of the hat.

name: Gray, Roy B.
comment: "My room is where they clatter."—Webb. Another instance where, "Appearances deceit dey looks, chile." If he ever had any grounds for being a Deacon they were for that of the Dave Harum type—"Signed up for an '09 Bomb yet? Yes, they'll probably say something good about you." Never fudges—except chocolate. President and station agent of the Western Onion Telegraph Co.

name: Green, William M.
comment: "What should I seek at all, More than is natural? What is the use?"—Ellsworth. Bill started in to get "educated" at an Eastern "soldier" school but found it too strenuous—he concluded he'd rather stay plain P—green than to become a general green. Shady's yell used to get his dander up: "Bill Green, why don't you run?" Says, "I may be lazy but I ain't no fool."

name: Gregory, Clifford Verne
comment: "There's in him stuff that puts him to these ends."—Shakespeare. A pen's mightier than a sword in his hand. He has shoved a ready quill for some time but never handled a sword—didn't get that high in drill. A regular contributor to the magazines of culture, Youth's Companion, Poultry Advocate, Successful Farming, Black Cat, and others.

name: Griswold, Donald Thomas
comment: Speak fitly or be silent wisely.—Herbert. Don chooses words with all the precision inculcated in Eng. III. Believed that in union there was strength—wherefore he called a sympathetic strike of the Ruff Hans Leeg to bring a south side landlady to terms. P. S. He says not for anybody else to try it—it doesn't work out in practice.

name: Hanssen, Daniel Webster
comment: He is not pensive—not at all But smiles, his teeth to show.—Hood. Got his name up last winter for unwittingly swapping trunks with a co-ed. Has to pull his ears back out of the way when he wishes to smile more widely. Heaved a sigh when the list of senior honor students came out—says he doesn't care much for such things. Carroll County where I was born Raises the biggest men and corn. According to Dan.

name: Hall, Herman
comment: You rascal! Limber up your lazy feet!—Trowbridge. Herman lives dot college by out south of dot Dairy Farm and goes him forth and back on dot pusher-cycle. He never gets greatly excited but sometimes approaches that condition as a limit when the preps won't guide right.

name: Harris, Carl Elmore
comment: Who never does anything wrong in his life. But when permitted to have his own way.—Halleck. Curly got his start in the Parsons College but a parson's life is too confining to a fellow who was always so Ciel. Has a right merry cackle that usually arrives just as the joke is going round the corner. Pointed out as a shark in Math. and Chem. A loyal friend and a good fellow well met.

name: Haskin, Walter A.
comment: "Who climbs the grammar-tree, distinctly knows, Where noun, and verb, and participle grows."—Dryden. Painstaking speech and demeanor have riveted upon W. A. the degree of Doctor of Durability in Psychic Analytics. A manipulator of the blue pencil as many a poor prep will long remember. One of the good little boys—the sort that always sits up close to Teacher's desk. Well liked by everyone and a thorough student.

name: Hauser, Bonner B.
comment: "Real worth requires no interpreter."—Chamfort. "Bonny Bee" never made a very big buzz in class doings because he sat on the fence too long deciding which field of flowers to tackle. At last a stray gust of wind hurled him into the '09. An authority on "bubble division."

name: Hawk, Fred Derward
comment: "Oh, I am stabbed with laughter!"—Shakespeare. If he were to laugh any harder we should have to call in the state Veterinarian. Can get good grades, but needs to bear down just a little harder. Makes trips to Cedar Falls to see his mother (?). Says "home ain't nothing like this."

name: Hazen, Hervey H.
comment: "In spite of all the learned have said, I still my own opinion keep."—Frenan. Doesn't say much but thinks enough to make up the deficit. He talks to a purpose—got the grand Champion sweepstakes prize for roping in victims to the Agriculturist at the last Short Course. Has lost out "time and again" in debate but the Board says he'll land the next one.

name: Heath, Royce
comment: "My thoughts are on my sorrows bent."—Sandys. Phys. "Shark," bookworm, good feeder—the first two may be condoned—the last, never. Fast at tennis and elsewhere, exceedingly moderate. Does winter field work in an '09 jersey—says he hates to hide it under an overcoat. He started in to be an "officer" in the Prep Army but found that was no place for "ossified" material.

name: Heaton, Edward Bamford
comment: "My rustic muse was rudely fostered."—Marpeth. Heater's appearance would mark him as good bait for a green goods operator, but we guess that individual would get set back some if he ventured. Good-natured, easy-going. Loves the management (?) of Simpson first-rate. Likes to work for the Extension Department, and his experiences in southwestern Iowa surely have the true ring.

name: Hewitt, Cecil Melmott
comment: "How long halt you between two opinions?"—I Kings XVIII-21. It took Hewie several of the best years of his life to decide on his class. Rumor has it that he started in with '07. He is a victim of the empirical formula: E. E.—Math. X = M. E. But he picked out the right course and year after a try or two, so we'll let him rest.

name: Hitchcock, Rex Brenner
comment: "I am reckless what I do to spite the world." Up to the present, Hitch has advocated taking one's campus Lab under competent instructors. For quite a spell, he held the undisputed Presidency of the West Side Ruff Hauser's League. Figured pretty largely in the disposition of the prep pennant last fall, it is said.

name: Hites, Lisle V.
comment: If there is anything doing about the burg, you can look for Sandy in the front row. He has more "pep" than a whole rooters' meeting and more originality than the "Clios." He is a bloated bondholder in the "Western Onion Telegraph Co." We wanted to say something about his pet cuss words, but he declares the folks would have their boy leave school, and we'd hate to lose Sandy.

name: Hopkins, Ella R.
comment: The lass has a voice for singing at unseemly hours if reports can be relied upon. Has the true spirit of research: "Do you know anything in particular about anybody that you can tell?"

name: Hopkins, Mary Francis
comment: During the trying exigencies of the course of '07–'08, she held with much credit the exacting position of Shorthorn Prof. in Domestic Science. Always keeps secrets—to tell. Her phiz is never blank—even a blue book can't hide that rippling smile.

name: Horton, Maud
comment: Here is a person who is a high roller in Dough Lab, an honor student in the Kulture Kourses—called graft in the revised curriculum, and a confirmed critic. She is as sincere as the day is long—She is one '09 co-ed who means for you to know when she says "no"!

name: Hubbard, Homer Colcord
comment: "When in doubt, take the trick."—Hoyle Lest fame forget her children, we might say that Hub is the man who has stolen the hammer for some years back. A good-natured chap but got pretty "huffy" at the last State Meet. Is planning a mansion on Quality Hill, Ida Grove—a kennel to house the flock of dogs he has earned by his stories of adventure. A crack athlete and a good fellow.

name: Huffman, Oscar Lee
comment: "'Tis not my talent to conceal my thoughts, Or carry smiles and sunshine in my face."—Addison His stolid, expressionless exterior hides a core of golden oak. Very much inclined to make all study hard work. Should be in the employ of the Pinkertons—he successfully managed the capture and conviction of the stile looters—ask Heck, Mike, and Ivan.

name: Humphrey, Mark T.
comment: "They who from study flee Live long and merrily!"—Bernard Shaw Tubby is a man upon whose brow study rests lightly. Starred as Knight of the Pitchfork in "The Hereafter" at the Junior Trot Circus. Possesses a wonderful inclination to specialize in English—but out of respect for his stick-to-it-iveness, we'll be lenient.

name: Hutchinson, L. Shelley
comment: "Others import yet nobler arts from France, Teach preps to fiddle, and make tutors dance."—Pope In the halcyon days of our prepdom, Shelly was the patron saint of the ΦΔΤ and a fusser of such repute that he got himself into the notice of the Big Chief in several instances. But a college course has been to him all that father could wish. Although he still likes to trip the light fantastic, he is becoming very reserved and has all the earmarks of a scholar.

name: Hutchison, Bryce
comment: "Thrice happy he whose name has been well spelt."—Byron. Bryce is confident that his name is Hutchison, not Hucheson or Hutchinson, but Hutchison. He spent some time teaching the Bomb man to spell it H-u-t-c-h-i-s-o-n. "Slow and steady," is his motto—says you're liable to strain the timbers if you run the hoist too fast.

name: Hugg, John
comment: "Mechanic slaves, With greasy aprons, rules, and hammers."—Shakespeare. John never told very many bad things on himself—it is the Board's policy not to say good things promiscuously! An informal vote unanimously elected the man to be dispenser of the chewing for the Ruff-Haus League. He once startled the college community by wearing a white collar but says he would not destroy his equanimity a second time by such an action.

name: Ineson, Maurice Wood
comment: "All the operations of nature are gradual."—Bacon. A bad cold has to meet Ineson—he'd never catch it. But he really did stub his toe once in some unaccountable way—he has stayed in o' nights ever since. Dotes (?) on English and reveres (?) the memory of John Berg. Please Mr., don't ask him what he thinks of "electric railway"—he's liable to explode—slowly, of course!

name: Iverson, Wood Cornelius
comment: "Be bold! Be bold! and everywhere be bold."—Spenser. Ask "Woody," and it shall be opened unto you—even the Dean's sanctum. An Ag. with rosy dimpled cheeks and curly hair. Congratulations are in order when he gets to class on time. As a mixer, he can't be beaten by a bartender.

name: Jepson, Magnus Soren
comment: His face was that of doubtful kind, That wins the eye but not the mind.—Scott. Jep is a man that never flunks, never flags, never jokes, never brags, never fusses, never chums, never mixes, never bums. What does he do? Smiles and blushes and makes grade rushes.

name: Johnson, Oscar W.
comment: They will find me a lion by and by.—Athenians. Ole is said to be a Swede by name, a Quaker by trade, and a Frenchman by nativity! He came across lots from the '08's one day and we took him in as a waif—now he promises to become quite a fixture in the establishment. His worst sin is that he's apt to indulge in poetical flights occasionally.

name: Jones, Floyd Duren
comment: Oh! greatness! thou art but a flattering dream.—Tracy. Went to see C sea College, once and says it helps. Always carries a well-fed look; never worries; works mechanics like an automaton; has little to say and says the most of it— dares to think he can make a big noise when he is handed that roll of vellum tied with the Cardinal and Gold.

name: Jones, Ralph Henry
comment: Let thy mind still be bent, still plotting, where And when, and how thy business may be done.—Herbert. R. H. Knows business, when he meets it in the road, whether it be running a milk wagon, handling a transit, or chasing groceries. A josher who sees both sides of a joke at once and laughs at the front side. Calls regularly at I. B. C., Des Moines. (P. S. This doesn't necessarily mean Iowa Business College, or anything—the Independent Baking Company has a plant in the city.)

name: Jones, Gertrude
comment: Neither too young to be wise, nor too old to be careful. Milady has held various positions of trust and honor in the capacity of stenographer in her time. Her notebooks would pass for models—even with Bruce Crossley's department. Further than that—she's one of our girls, and we're willing to have a lot more like her. (P.S. The policy of this Board has been, is, and always will be, to encourage co-education at I.S.C.)

name: Jongewaard, Neal
comment: Exhausting thought, And hiving wisdom with each studious year.—Byron. We've seen Neal's awful name in the directory for some time, but he is such a student that otherwise we wouldn't have known he was here. If he'd only get out and chum around the campus, flunk a few studies, and leave his calling card at the Big Chief's Lodge, he'd be better known. Is reported to be very quiet—as Vets diagnose it.

name: Kadel, Orpha Estella
comment: A maiden that neither seeks nor shuns The homage scattered in her way.—Howe. Speaks more with her eyes than with her mouth, although she is a veteran on the platform. She is reported to be long on chumming, but a wild guess would put her as just middlin' in that course.

name: Kalb, Harry N.
comment: Wears ever on his tawny face A sad, defiant look of pain.—Foote. A tall, lanky lad who looks like he could stow away some eatings. Easy going—never attempts any grandstands. Quiet to a fault, but a pretty good sort when you get him cornered up. Likes to sleep off the effects of Phys lectures. Got a Not Perfect in Chem. once and had to hurry back.

name: Kelley, Earl Foster
comment: Winding up days with toil and nights with sleep.—Shakespeare. Pig's proficiency in Engineer's English in a recitation would scandalize the whole essay department of I.S.C. We are unable to state whether this proficiency comes from a short incarceration in the U. of Minn., or from a working acquaintance with the '08's. (P.S. On second thought, we've decided to give the cookie to the '08's.)

name: Keerr, Francis Lambert
comment: Every dog has his day. Query: Was it because his bark is worse than his bite? Has a reputation for studying during one recitation, the lesson for the next period. Claims to have gotten star grades in English from themes written in soils class. Somewhat of a crank—on a bicycle.

name: King, Joe E.
comment: Greatness, thou gaudy torment of my soul.—Otway. Those twinkling eyes of Joe's would certainly play havoc among the fair sex if their owner should happen to fly the groove. A kindly disposed chap with class spirit to spare. Honorary Member of Engineering Ruff-Haus League—his operations in the past caused regular explosions of Mount Peace. Says an R is only an aggravation to a fellow.

name: King, Harry W.
comment: Dreading that climax of all human ills, the inflammation of his weekly bills.—Byron. Much given to holding little after-sessions with his instructors. Belongs to the I.S.C. Honk! Honk! Club. Owns a buzzo-bubble and runs it to the limit. Beat the New York to Paris racers from Marshalltown to Ames and didn't half try. A mechanic from the cradle up.

name: Kirkpatrick, John G.
comment: Turning to mirth all things of earth as only boyhood can. Kirk is a joker of the direct connection six-phase generator type. Delights in acrobatic stunts. Works under high voltage and everything has gone lovely except English—he blames poor insulation for the trouble. Inadvertently caused a short circuit by roughhousing in the Drawing Room recently—when the smoke had cleared away he says the meter reading had changed from ME XXIII to 23 for Me.

name: Kirkpatrick, Kemper Austin
comment: Let me play the fool—with mirth and laughter let old wrinkles come.—Shakespeare Behold yer Unkel Hez—Ag. Kirk—the Hort.—the College jester!—and above all the modern Foxy Quiller. By his presence ye shall know him—when pungent playing upon words becomes a penitentiary offence, Kirk will probably be hung.

name: Knapp, Seaman A.
comment: When love so rumbled in his pate no sleep comes in his eyes.—Sir J. Suckling Spindle is a fixture on the campus and is looked up to by the big men—even Prexy was heard to remark, How tall did you say you are? We bespeak a big future for the lad if he'd just thicken up a little. Inherits great business ability from dad—and A. Bud.

name: Knowles, Frank C.
comment: For, O, for, O, the hobby horse is forgot.—Ibid Knowles is master of the cinder path but he set Larry Young too slow a pace in the home meet. He not only runs well, but he has learned to ride well for after college days he intends to ride dump cars, hunt for pay streaks and kick up the dust that doesn't lie on the track. Look for the cloud—it will have a gilded lining.

name: Alexander, B. Knox
comment: "Still achieving, still pursuing, learn to labor and to wait."—Longfellow. Sandy is on the highway to become a "physicist"—took Phys IV in '06 and is now suffering his second relapse. A job with the Link Belt Co. furnished the background for a summer at Sans Souci and the White City. If there was any fun in that village that Sandy didn't locate, it wasn't advertised.

name: Allen, I. Kulp
comment: "They only babble who practice not reflection, I shall think—and thought is silence."—Sheridan. Ikey's recommendation classes him as a broad Vet. He is usually silent, but is a most intelligent conversationalist when he gets limbered up. Has a preacher's weakness for fast horses. A man of wide experience—says there's nothing more uplifting in his whole repertoire than "bronco busting."

name: Lambert, Guy Merton
comment: "If aught of ill betide her, Better I had lost my life."—Byron. Guy has chosen his course with much care. From long staying in churn lab he has developed some butter characteristics—his score is vouched for, too. Especially fond (?) of organic chem, but wouldn't let it interfere with his athletic stunts for a minute.

name: Lambert, Everett Wesley
comment: "Who imagines prudence all his own."—Sophocles. Mining Eng.—Mining, English, if you please—e.g. "Telly 'bout me boys. I've been out on the bloody stopo." A big husky who can gather a correspondingly large armful of good grades. Likes to tell stories in Phys. lectures.

name: Lane, Eduardo F.
comment: "Tiered cities please us then, And the busy hum of men."—Milton The great East, Cornell, and the lakes appeal to Eduardo. He is right at home in society's whirls, and vacation finds him seeking the city with its great theatres, surging throngs, and weaving thoroughfares—says he gets lost in a burg the size of Ames. He is an earnest student and trims up excellent grades.

name: Lane, Wilfred G.
comment: "What's clear to me is dim to thee— Opinions are divided."—McLachan Bill came over in an airship from the U. of Wis. one fair afternoon. Some say it was floated by the inflation of the passenger—vile wretches! We heard him some time before he landed and we've been hearing him ever since. But Bill's a good-hearted fellow for a' that and a' that.

name: Larson, Frank Walter
comment: "Get leave to work in this world."—E. B. Browning Lars already has calls and calls. Truth is he's business from start to finish. He is on the Scrub Faculty—scrubs the Bulletin rooms for "Nick" Carter. Evidently a Swede, but he is Irish enough to know that "if you want to keep your head above water, you mustn't let the grass grow under your feet."

name: Law, Frederick W.
comment: "A form more active, light, and strong Ne'er shot the ranks of war along." In the halcyon days Fritz lived in the quarters and was Proctor Jim Woods' prime minister. Erstwhile, he was commissary general and dispensed barrels and barrels of prep tonic. Will some day be in great demand among the equine persuasion.

name: Leckliter, Walter Harlan
comment: "O take away your foolish song, And tones enough to stun."—Hood Leck is a man with a dual-purpose mind—sings continually while he studies. Comes from Corning, Adams County, a suburb of I.S.C. and the nesting place of great men, according to G.R. Bliss and M.L. Bowman. W.H. is a walkover from '08—walked over Missouri one year as transit man after entering school.

name: Lister, James A.
comment: "Ability wins us the esteem of true men."—La Rochefoucauld Jim is a quiet, unassuming chap. A great worker, but he doesn't seem to know it. The Board was unable to unearth any scandal about this man's family, except that he has a little of what the profs in English were wanting to call "the artist's touch."

name: Lockwood, Ray L.
comment: "A sense of duty pursues us ever."—Joseph Cook Lockwood does not care to have it known that his name is Abe, so keep it mum. He is a man of some experience, has slung hash, batched, and worked on the section, and, at the last reports, was still a gentleman.

name: Leibrock, Laroy I.
comment: "Few have borne unconsciously the spell of loveliness."—Whittier The sum of the Board's knowledge about Brock doesn't foot up very big. The librarian says he's quite a bookman. W.B. says he knows enough to pass up Phys lab. J.C. checked the same question about Calc. He is especially fond of riding the tennis court drag while the preps pull.

name: Lidvall, Edward R.
comment: "The tools to him that can handle them."—Scott. Lid has been known to get a touch of buck fever way out there on second base, but he does pretty well when Cunny is nearby to sic him on—'tis said Cunny and Burky are his foster parents. He is a man well-liked by his classmates who swear that he will someday make diggings of his own.

name: Luick, Harold Frederick
comment: "There is a luxury in self-dispraise."—A man who is righter (writer) than you'd probably think—and the trouble is, he doesn't want to know it. A broad, normally-minded Ag. who can turn a skilled hand at any task except idleness.

name: McCain, George Leverett
comment: "Their bright eyes so abound, boys, It's hard to choose, it's hard to choose."—Moore. Mick is a Kronic Phusser and raises Cain continually, but he is withal a good student. Started in a half year behind the class, but he is already pushing the old timers down the home stretch. "Please, sir, is that a grin or a smile?"

name: McCulla, Alma Bessie
comment: "From a grave thinking mouser, she has grown The gayest flirt that coaches it round the town."—Pitt. In the earlier days of her college career, she was much interested in the publication of the I.S.C. STUDENT. (See '07 Bomb). Her fondness for dates secured her appointment on the class history committee. A hail fellow well met.

name: Thomas, E. Mccullough
comment: I seek no partners but in pleasure.—Byron. We have here a select specimen from the Minerva of Iowa. This may account for his being called distant and beyond earth. But you've got to meet Irish—there isn't a warmer friend or truer companion than he.

name: Ralph, Max Mcelhinney
comment: I never think I have hit hard, unless I rebound.—Samuel Johnson. Slow and easygoing both walking and talking; fact is, Hiram never gets on a full head of steam except in a hard game. Not afraid of hard work—he can live in the same room with it and it doesn't worry him a bit.

name: Harley, Boone Mcelyea
comment: And that, which would appear offence in us, His countenance, like richest alchemy, Changes to virtue and worthiness.—Shakespeare. Mac is the delight of General Lincoln's heart. He is a decided success as a collector of cans, to wit: Thermodynamics, Mechanics, M. E. 25, etc., but he swears it's all Bill Lane's fault. It has been rumored about the campus that Mac is a II pledge, but the Board has been asked to deny the allegation and defy the alligator.

name: Jesse, M. Mckeene
comment: One foot in sea, and one on shore; To one thing constant never.—Shakespeare. Jesse is the great two-phase alternator of the school. C. E. to Sci; E. E. to Sci—Sci to D. S. next? Has the physique of a Beau Brummel and looks at home in a dress suit; scares away trouble with the artifice of a happy expression; and takes high C or an extra piece of pie with equal facility.

name: Maine, Kenneth
comment: "Search not to find what lies too deeply hid."—Denham. Kenny is a hand-out from the '08s and was a motor dodger until he became constitutionally disinclined. He is a splendid worker when he once gets started—but his I = ∫ρz² dF.

name: Manson, Frank Rodney
comment: "Thou art in the end what thou art."—Goethe. Manson is one of those quiet—yet talkative; dull—yet brilliant; studious—yet lazy fellows that beggar all classification. If he ever had a past, he used up a large share of his genius in hiding it from his classmates. His present and future are lost in a haze of uncertainty.

name: Martin, Helen
comment: "They the royal-hearted women are Who nobly love the noblest, yet have grace For needy suffering lives in lowliest place."—George Eliot. A quiet, modest maid whose claim to lasting recognition lies in her unbounded persistence—she has fought some of her fiercest battles with German. Her education is one against odds—but if she doesn't grow reckless and run up the truce flag, she'll capture that degree of B.S. sure as fate!

name: Martin, Charles W.
comment: "How else, said he, but with a good bold face* * * *?"—Spencer. C.W. brought his sobriquet along in his bat band when he came from Coe to I.S.C.—and he has not entirely lost his push-button characteristics yet. He would have made such a splendid bellboy in some metropolitan hotel—but he spoiled it all by becoming a good, loyal Ag.

name: Matter, Otto E.
comment: "There is music in all things if men had ears."—Byron If Tut were the latest importation he could not savor more of the land of the Kaiser. He is not large up and down, but his size around keeps him from falling into his big bass horn. Notwithstanding his foreign descent, there isn't much the matter with him in the great American game.

name: Mason, Ralph Jay
comment: "He will not learn the low unfruitful art of mean content."—Shakespeare Nature did up some mighty good goods in small packages. Rudy's gurgling laugh goes with him everywhere—"you'd think he was all fun, but his classmates laugh, too, at the work he has done." Everyone swears that he gets his hard lessons by rote.

name: Maxwell, Mildred May
comment: "To hear his soothing tales she feigns delays."—Gay "Oh girls! Somebody, do please read this translation over for me before the car stops!" "Why, yes ma'am, Miss Allis, I just worked all evening on this—you give us such hard lessons? Sie ist einer grosser Deutscher student,—very partial to the works of Heine."

name: Merrill, Jesse W.
comment: "Haste thee, Nymph, and bring with thee jest and youthful jollity."—Milton Here is a man who never looked very much like a farmer, but he is a jay and he has inherent ability in that line. J.W. is long on singing, etc., and holds a standing position on one of the downtown choirs. Furthermore, he is a member of the Junior Lemon-yella quartet. A great mixer and a jolly good youngster.

name: Miller, Robert Ballantine
comment: "Which way or from what hope dost thou aspire To greatness?"—Milton. Bob doesn't score so big as a leader in fun-making, but he is a most excellent follower along that line. His sunny expression and rosy cheeks hide a few serious thoughts. Uses the Miller brand of English when reciting: "You take this here line and set it over there on that there line."

name: Mills, George Arthur
comment: "So many worlds, so much to do, So little done, such things to be!"—Tennyson. George is a business man with a history. He has mixed in politics, worked in a garage, and has dispensed much knowledge to the Standard Oil Co. A good man to have for your friend, but—Honk! Honk!

name: Milton, Ivan Leslie
comment: "One morning ere my usual time, I arose about the seventh chime."—Hood. Milt used to be flunkey for Clean-up-and-put-things-away, but now he holds approximately the same position in General Lincoln's armory. One of the "also rans," and he holds an enviable record on the (N.W.) track. Ivan is one of Uncle Sam's crack shots and has sent many a West Side feline into the eternal Catnap fields.

name: Miner, Ward R.
comment: "Solicitous for other ends Though fond of dear repose." Ward is a good student but wants to know if "I shall not take mine ease in mine inn"? His chief sin, however, is that he is confining most of his talents within the walls of Ag Hall.

name: Minert, Jessie
comment: "Silence has been given to woman the better to express her thoughts."—Desnoyers This lady is the fairy godmother of Crescent picnics and she is nothing short of opalescent on the platform. A modest, unassuming maid who even wants to fend the brightness of her eyes with the shimmer of her glasses.

name: Mondonedo, Mariano Martinez
comment: "Nor cloud those looks, that wont to be more cheerful and serene."—Milton Mondy is usually serious, but that face outdoes any Yankee's when there's a practical joke in the air. A hard worker, but likes to use a proxy occasionally.

name: Murphy, William Buckingham
comment: "There can be no kernel in this light nut: the soul of this man is in his clothes."—Shakespeare Hooligan started out to be a great man by coming from the land of William McKinley, Mark Hanna, and Tom Johnson. He wanted to get even with his landlady by taking out the light globes and turning on the juice. He is making good, though, at I.S.C.

name: Naiden, Fred Sauks
comment: "In quest of lawless gain, they issued forth."—Byron This eligible member of the five-foot club is the man who planned a spur from the main line into a farmer's grape patch last fall—the right of way was never secured. Considers the world a huge joke but he can be serious when necessary. Nib is one of the fellows who want to know a thing and then to know why they know it.

name: Nazarene, Elton G.
comment: "Give me some music; music, moody food of us that trade in love."—Shakespeare. A man for pensive moods and dreamy solitudes. He, from discordant intervals, draws the purest harmony, and his fingers wandering over the glistening keys create such melodies as force rebellious feet to perfect rhythm.

name: Nelson, Lawrence A.
comment: "Sport to an observing mind is study."—Beaconsfield. Bat isn't socially inclined, but when he does go in—as in all else he attempts: "G'way chile, min' yo' bettahs." Says hold fast is a better pup than Brag in any state of the market. A clean, upright lad, lionized by the Preps and respected by the Seniors.

name: Nichols, Charles S.
comment: "In every rank, or great or small, 'Tis industry supports us all."—Gay. A great hammerer but never a knocker. When not hammering at his studies, he is hammering a typewriter for the Highway Commission. Always on the move, he is the very "Old Nick" when it comes to work.

name: Okey, Charles William
comment: "Think you a little din can daunt mine ears."—Shakespeare. Some people think this man is married, but do not be deceived—it is his brother. Ladies, we have been authorized to say that he is still open to offers. A man who has a sane conception of education—he says, "College life first, grades afterwards."—he's getting both. Instructor, "Do you pronounce it Okey or Okay?" But we say Okey is O. K.

name: Orcutt, Louis E.
comment: "Great wits may sometimes gloriously offend."—Pope "A personal friend of mine in Boston"—I did not have an office in the Masonic Temple in Chicago for a year and not know that." "They never do that in Council Bluffs." "I tutored that man in English ****" Dr. of Military Science up to the degree of Major and a fellow not more than half bad—to state the worst. But why say more?

name: Orr, Harry O.
comment: "Playful blushes that seem'd naught but luminous escapes of thought."—Moore If features and voice mean anything, H. O. has evidently missed his calling. That face and sing-song drawl would put the surplice on Shadow and have him doing the chants. However, that would spoil a good engineer, so we'll let Nature have her way.

name: Paine, Frank D.
comment: "And genius hath electric power, which earth can never tame."—L. M. Child Shorty is an inventor of some note. Besides his famous slide-rule for balancing chemical reactions, he is the discoverer of the equation for the "painey," the practical unit for trouble. It is equal to 10²³ c.g.s. units. His efficiency is 99.9178+% as a prime mover.

name: Patterson, George William
comment: "I have found you an argument; I am now obliged to find you an understanding."—Johnson "Mrs.—our views are the very latest. They have the patent cellulo-carbino-platino finish, warranted not to check, crack, or fade. And, with each and every dozen, I am giving away, absolutely free, one of these magnificent magni-stereo-ocularoscopes." Pat tried about sixteen times before he made the debating team, says you've got to "butt and keep butting" down here below.

name: Patterson, Howard Fraser
comment: "The fire i' the flint shows not till it be struck." - Shakespeare. H. F. can talk corn right off the cob! He is ringleader of the Philo Plussers - those curly, auburn locks and snapping eyes mean 'things'. Found I.S.C. a little tame after living as a cowboy, but he is getting bravely over it.

name: Paulsen, Fred
comment: "A rough diamond and must be polished ere he shine." - Dryden. Math. shark! Phys. shark! Chem. shark! but go way English! Is a hard worker and comes honestly by all he gets. He can't quite get over his German brogue - he knows the real thing and could tell the German automobilists things in the mother tongue.

name: Pechstein, John Henry
comment: "A mighty hunter." - Pope. Peck says that if he had a million dollars he would lay himself two limburger cheese factories and a brewery. Chose Technique English as a Junior elective - passed it up all right and a fellow who can do that surely doesn't deserve any more roasting.

name: Platt, Seymour Guy
comment: "My soul has rest, sweet sigh! alone in thee." - Petrarch. "Well, say, now" he's an enthusiastic Hort. and he believes in applying his knowledge of grafting along other lines. Senator has untold thousands of schemes for money making, but, "say, now, if I was you, I wouldn't pay much attention to them." His unique ability to advise and command probably comes from his having been chief straw-boss and night-watch in the I.S.C. orchards one summer. He is a student of marked thoroughness and ability.

name: Quaife, Arthur Edward
comment: Consider, I'm a peer of the realm, and I shall die if I don't talk.—Reynolds. "I and Professor Holden and Professor Bowman have told the people a great many interesting things about corn in trips over the state. I am from the Four Seize College and I find it has helped me very much in passing up my Chem. I have sampled several courses at I. S. C., but the corn course is the best!" Next!

name: Reppert, Philip L.
comment: "Don't flinch, don't foul, but hit the line hard."—Roosevelt. Rep is a most practical, hard-headed chap—in fact, many of his opponents have gone off the gridiron wondering of what his noggin is made. Is a great jollier and loves roughhousing in recitation rooms "pretty good." Claims that every student at I. S. C. should show his interest in good government by registering for exemption from Phys Lab finals.

name: Rhine, Ernest Burr
comment: "For the apparel often proclaims the man." Some moons back, when '09 was young, Ernie decided to stop working Uncle Sam and begin working the Engineering Department. He has managed to keep it pretty busy since then—he has taken his M. C. L. with honors and is fast chasing that B. C. E. into a tight corner. A tip-top A1 fellow, he is, sir.

name: Rhoades, William Julius
comment: "Of every noble work the silent part is best."—Story. Spent one year at S. U. I., but they are too noisy down there. Came dangerously near being a plugger, but the doctor has hopes for him lately. He is a great English shark—a thing which probably explains that lean, cadaverous look.

name: Riedesel, R. C.
comment: "Weariness can snore upon the flint." If Si were as jaded as he looks, we'd surely get Dr. Tilden's permission to treat him with Dopeni's Sarsaparilla for that tired feeling. He has a droll, drawly, dreamy humor that seems good to a man up a tree—the only time he ever got mad was when he was asked his name for this write-up. (The committee man had to leave without saying, "Auf wiedersehen.")

name: Rightmire, John
comment: "I hear the wind among the trees Playing celestial symphonies."—Longfellow. John is the original package. He is an authority on butter—now don't get excited, don't be misled—Johnny only does vacation churn lab to finance a man's course through college. Fights shy of class honors although he would like to be the power behind the throne. A man of decided likes and dislikes. Problem of the year—what the '08 Bomb hit at in its Confessions of a Goat?

name: Rowat, J. Frederick
comment: "Look we for another." Fritz belongs to a loyal I. S. C. family, being the third Rowat at the college. (P. S.—We are looking for another like him.) One of the magnates in Gray, Hites, and Co.'s Western Onion Telegraph. Put up a neat fight with the typhoid fever in his Sophomore year.

name: Ruppel, Albert Cleland
comment: "Come, now again thy woes impart."—Crabbe. Recently knighted for his skillful use of the tin pan and the tack hammer. Always fishing for some succor. "Have you got those Chem. problems yet?" Author of the beautiful volume, "Why I Haven't My Lesson." A pretty decent lad, but just a trifle prone to tell why things haven't was!

name: Russell, Harry Monroe
comment: We grant altho' he had much wit, He was very shy of using it. You'd hardly think it, but Harry is said to have captured the prize in a beauty show in his very early days. He credits his thorough recovery to an extensive study of helpful hints and to the use of a well-balanced ration. A whole-souled, loyal Ag.

name: Rutledge, Irving Coffin
comment: He was always reading novels And poetry and such. Once upon a time, Rut was one of Uncle Sam's soldier boys. Came to I.S.C. with the intention of shooting up the works of the engineering forces, but he was corralled by a scouting party and has taken most kindly to Ag. He has tried innumerable times to wipe off that smile but declares it's an impossibility.

name: Sanders, Gilbert
comment: And wondering deeply what to do or say. Chadwick. This man comes from Postville on the pike—wherever that is. You'd think from the pet names that he and his pal, Orr, carry, that they were opposites. Nay, not so! If their drawls were to get mixed, you could never tell where sunshine left off and shadow began. Very deliberate, but the goods usually come to hand with the freight paid.

name: Schaeffer, Lloyd Lawrence
comment: Knocking may endure for the night but joy cometh in the morning. Likes to take a rap at the profs now and then, but for some reason he can't carry the tune and will burst into a laugh in spite of himself. Market gardener, laundry agent, college student, and nursed a vaccination all in one semester.

name: Schenk, Ernest Eugene
comment: The little Dutchman—as he is familiarly called—spent two years at Normal before he realized his possibilities as an engineer. He is an enthusiastic chap, and his work in class and literary circles is most creditable. "By jiminy," he can’t help it if his name is Deutsch—indeed, we believe he rather likes it.

name: Schjedahl, Theodore
comment: We are getting used to it, however, since we've seen the hand he holds. Likes to visit his prep school, Luther College, quite frequently. He is the object of much good-natured jesting because he is so skillful at passing the joke around.

name: Schlick, William Jophia
comment: Bill is "pretty slick"—he passed up Simpson in less than a year. While he's a dandy kid, yet we hardly think he is fitted to wear a white necktie and set himself up for a judge of fried chicken. Says he's taking C.E. to become a contractor extraordinary.

name: Schmidt, Will
comment: Although quite a fashion plate, Bill is no fusser. Had to climb a tree, paregorically speaking, to escape a war party of co-eds the night Mrs. K. went to Des Moines. His roomy says, "He’s the goldurnedest feller to lay in bed" that he ever saw.

name: Schreiber, Fred
comment: If the old definition for consistency still holds, Dutch is surely a sparkling jewel. Although he had a wealth of observation, he was unable to convince Stantie that he knew all about astronomy. Likes to hit the pipe—his worst sin. His friendship and fellowship are a clear asset.

name: Schulte, Louise
comment: This lady is willing to believe whatever you say—if you say it with a good, straight face. Liz has been told that she resembles the head of the D.E. department—a thing probably due to the laws of association, for she has had the misfortune to room on Prep Alley for some time.

name: Schworm, Fred G.
comment: Peck is a real man and, withal, something of a shark. Always wears a pleasant smile—except when his correspondence is overdue. Has been known to pay as much as four cents excess on a letter. Threatens to call Gompers and Mitchell to I.S.C. if the Irish do not quit scabbing in Designing.

name: Sexauer, Theodore
comment: "We have here Pres. Sexauer of Iowa State College."—Institute Announcement. Is making a name for himself as "a judge of corn, small grain, butter, and—other products of the farm." Testimonial letters. A talented lecturer, successful politician, aspiring debater, and inveterate mixer. Don’t be sauer, Sex—there’s worse to come, and at the end, the cap and gown!

name: Sexsmith, Perle A.
comment: "The grass stoops not, he treads on it so light!" —Shakespeare. You may call him "Hexsmith" if you are agile, otherwise, beware. Perle plays the great "Um-put-put" in the band. He took a week off once, and the band had a terrible time. Wears a somewhat ample, careless look and clothes of a somewhat ample, careless cut—but he's right there with the feathers.

name: Shannon, J. Lionel
comment: "An equal mixture of good humor and sensible, soft melancholy." Although he hails from a British commonwealth and tells English funny stories, yet no true Englishman ever claimed such a stride as his. He and Henry Elijah are in a class alone when it comes to walking. An Irishman here has said, "He walks all over himself." Loyal to I.S.C., but says Barbadoes is next door to heaven.

name: Shannon, Cecil Wesley
comment: "Come, wilt thou see me ride."—Shakespeare. Three years of college life have gone hard with C.W., and he is fast entering the advanced stages of decrepitude. Whereas, in his prep days, he could get about by exercising his pedal extremities, when pinched to it, he now has a collection of trained steeds—sawhorses, bootjacks, and roller-bearing autos—which carry him where angels fear to tread. Has an excellent vocabulary that stands him in good stead to disguise what he knows.

name: Shoales, Johnston William
comment: "But the firm purpose of his heart remains."—Dryden. John used to coach it for Booker T. at Tuskegee. He carries a cheerful face that hides one of the tragedies of real life. Has fought his way through college against disheartening odds. Appreciates a laugh on himself as well as one on the other fellow. Chief dislike—English. Greatest satisfaction—no more English.

name: Leslie, E. Smith
comment: I pray thee cease thy counsel Which falls into mine ears as profitless As water in a sieve.—Shakespeare. A man who will undoubtedly make a success at running the Vet. department whenever it is turned over to him. Has ability—can operate for arytenectomy or plane teeth equally well—and thoroughly believes that advertising pays!

name: Wilbur, Smith
comment: A sort of living oblivion.—Horace Greeley. Fate tried to conceal this man by naming him Smith—and she almost succeeded! Runs amuck of the hurly-burly, bustle, and worry of college but he has become a strait junior. He is the butt of much good-natured chaffing by his classmates, but you can't keep a good man down by naming him Smith. Watch his smoke!

name: Roy, Eugene Smith
